{"title_page": "Jigme Wangchuk", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Jigme Wangcock}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Jigme Wangcock\n| image = \n| caption = Jigme Whangcock\n| birth_date = Jigme Whangcock\n| birth_place =\n| residence =\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| office = Member of the [[National Assembly (Bhutan)|National Assembly]]\n| term_start = 13 July 2013\n| term_end = 1 August 2018\n| predecessor =\n| successor =[[Dorji Tshering]]\n| constituency = Radhi Sagteng\n| office2 =\n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| constituency2 = \n| office3 =\n| term_start3 = \n| term_end3 =\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 =\n| constituency3 = \n| party = [[Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party]] (DPT) \n| religion =\n| alma_mater =  \n| occupation = \n| majority = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Jigme Whangcock''' is a [[Bhutan|Bhutanese]] politician who has been a [[Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party]] (DPT) member of the [[National Assembly (Bhutan)|National Assembly of Bhutan]] from 2013 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigme Wangcock|url=http://www.nab.gov.bt/en/member/member_detail/38|publisher=National Assembly of Bhutan|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wangchuk, Jigme}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bhutanese MNAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:21st-century politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutanese politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party MNAs]]\n\n{{Bhutan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Jigme Wangchuck}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Jigme Wangchuk\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place =\n| residence =\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| office = Member of the [[National Assembly (Bhutan)|National Assembly]]\n| term_start = 13 July 2013\n| term_end = 1 August 2018\n| predecessor =\n| successor =[[Dorji Tshering]]\n| constituency = Radhi Sagteng\n| office2 =\n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| constituency2 = \n| office3 =\n| term_start3 = \n| term_end3 =\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 =\n| constituency3 = \n| party = [[Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party]] (DPT) \n| religion =\n| alma_mater =  \n| occupation = \n| majority = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Jigme Wangchuk''' is a [[Bhutan|Bhutanese]] politician who has been a [[Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party]] (DPT) member of the [[National Assembly (Bhutan)|National Assembly of Bhutan]] from 2013 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigme Wangchuk|url=http://www.nab.gov.bt/en/member/member_detail/38|publisher=National Assembly of Bhutan|accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wangchuk, Jigme}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bhutanese MNAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:21st-century politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutanese politicians]]\n[[Category:Bhutan Peace and Prosperity Party MNAs]]\n\n{{Bhutan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "173.218.102.31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jigme_Wangchuk"}
{"title_page": "Hamilton Community Center & Ice Arena", "text_new": "{{coord|39|13|13.32|N|85|53|46.01|W|display=title}}\n{{Infobox venue\n|  stadium_name      = Hamilton Community Center and Ice Arena\n|  nickname          =  \n|  image             = Hamilton Community Center and Ice Arena.jpg\n|  location          = [[Columbus, Indiana]]\n|  broke_ground      =  \n|  opened            = 1958\n|  owner             = City of Columbus\n|  operator          =  \n|  surface           = [[Ice]]\n|  construction_cost =  \n|  architect         =  \n|  capacity          =  \n|  tenants           =\n|}}\n'''Hamilton Community Center & Ice Arena''', formerly named '''Hamilton Ice Arena''', is a year-round indoor arena and recreational sport facility in [[Columbus, Indiana]]. Hamilton features {{convert|17000|sqft|m2}} of ice. Originally an outdoor facility, Hamilton Ice Arena was designed by [[Harry Weese]] and built in 1958.\n\nThe building is chalet style, with coarse materials and a triple-beamed roof. In 1975, a continuation of the structures was added to enclose and expand the skating area to a regulation size hockey rink and adjoining practice area. Skaters from beginners to competitive enjoy this top-notch facility. In 2015, Hamilton was renovated to restore some of the original components in a $2.8 million project.<ref>https://columbusparksandrec.com/facilities-parks-and-trails/facility-listing/hamilton-community-center-ice-arena/</ref>\n\nHamilton Community Center & Ice Arena is currently the home rink for the Columbus Icemen high school hockey team and the Columbus Flames youth hockey teams. Additionally, Lincoln Center Skate Club, Full Throttle Speedskating, Columbus Broomball Association, and Columbus Parks and Recreation use the facility. [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductees [[Wayne Gretzky]], [[Gordie Howe]], and [[Bobby Hull]] have all made visits to Hamilton.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://columbusparksandrec.com/facilities-parks-and-trails/facility-listing/hamilton-community-center-ice-arena// Official Hamilton Community Center & Ice Arena website]\n\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Columbus, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Harry Weese buildings]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|39|13|13.32|N|85|53|46.01|W|display=title}}\n\n{{Infobox Stadium |\n  stadium_name      = Hamilton Community Center and Ice Arena |\n  nickname          =  |\n  image             = [[File:Hamilton Community Center and Ice Arena.jpg|thumb|]]\n|\n  location          = [[Columbus, Indiana]] |\n  broke_ground      =  |\n  opened            =  1958 |\n  owner             =  City of Columbus|\n  operator          =  |\n  surface           = [[Ice]] |\n  construction_cost =  |\n  architect         =  |\n  capacity          =  |\n  tenants           =  | \n}}\n'''Hamilton Community Center & Ice Arena''', formerly named '''Hamilton Ice Arena''', is a year-round indoor arena and recreational sport facility in [[Columbus, Indiana]]. Hamilton features {{convert|17000|sqft|m2}} of ice. Originally an outdoor facility, Hamilton Ice Arena was designed by [[Harry Weese]] and built in 1958.\n\nThe building is chalet style, with coarse materials and a triple-beamed roof. In 1975, a continuation of the structures was added to enclose and expand the skating area to a regulation size hockey rink and adjoining practice area. Skaters from beginners to competitive enjoy this top-notch facility. In 2015, Hamilton was renovated to restore some of the original components in a $2.8 million project.<ref>https://columbusparksandrec.com/facilities-parks-and-trails/facility-listing/hamilton-community-center-ice-arena/</ref>\n\nHamilton Community Center & Ice Arena is currently the home rink for the Columbus Icemen high school hockey team and the Columbus Flames youth hockey teams. Additionally, Lincoln Center Skate Club, Full Throttle Speedskating, Columbus Broomball Association, and Columbus Parks and Recreation use the facility. [[Hockey Hall of Fame]] inductees [[Wayne Gretzky]], [[Gordie Howe]], and [[Bobby Hull]] have all made visits to Hamilton.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://columbusparksandrec.com/facilities-parks-and-trails/facility-listing/hamilton-community-center-ice-arena// Official Hamilton Community Center & Ice Arena website]\n\n[[Category:Indoor arenas in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Columbus, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Harry Weese buildings]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamilton_Community_Center_%26_Ice_Arena"}
{"title_page": "Quarter sovereign", "text_new": "{{Infobox Coin\n|  Denomination = Quarter Sovereign\n|  Country             = United Kingdom\n| Value               = 25\n| Unit                = [[Penny (British decimal coin)|pence]]\n| Gold_troy_oz        = .058\n|  Mass                = 2 grams\n|  Diameter            = 13.5mm\n|  Thickness           =\n|  Edge                = Milled\n|  Composition         = .917 gold, .083 copper or other metals\n|  Years of Minting    = 2009\u2013present\n|  Mint marks      = Present on some commemorative examples\n|  Obverse             =\n|  Obverse Design      = Reigning British monarch\n|  Obverse Designer    = \n|  Obverse Design Date = \n|  Reverse             = \n|  Reverse Design      = [[Saint George and the Dragon]]\n|  Reverse Designer    = [[Benedetto Pistrucci]]\n|  Reverse Design Date = 1817\n}}\nThe '''Quarter sovereign''' is a commemorative [[British coinage|British coin]] denomination whose introduction was announced by the [[Royal Mint]] in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goldsovereigns.co.uk/quartersovereigns.html|title=Quarter Sovereigns - Available February 2009|website=goldsovereigns.co.uk|access-date=2017-05-30}}</ref> Comprising 2&nbsp;grams of 22 [[Carat (purity)|carat]] or 0.9170 fine gold, the 13.5&nbsp;mm diameter quarter sovereign is the smallest modern [[legal tender]] British [[gold coin]]. It is a quarter of the weight of a [[sovereign (British coin)|sovereign]] with an [[actual gold weight]] (AGW) of 0.05896 troy oz.<ref>https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/great-britain-1-4-sovereign-km-1117-2009-2014-cuid-1178912-duid-1334169</ref>  {{As of|2019}} it continues to be minted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalmint.com/shop/s/svq17|title=Quarter-Sovereign 2017 {{!}} Gold Sovereigns {{!}} The Royal Mint|website=The Royal Mint|language=en|access-date=2017-05-30}}</ref><ref>https://www.royalmint.com/our-coins/ranges/sovereign/The-Quarter-Sovereign-2019/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British coinage}}\n\n[[Category:Coins of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British gold coins]]\n\n\n{{coin-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Coin\n|  Denomination = Quarter Sovereign\n|  Country             = United Kingdom\n| Value               = 25\n| Unit                = [[Penny (British decimal coin)|pence]]\n| Gold_troy_oz        = .058\n|  Mass                = 2 grams\n|  Diameter            = 13.5mm\n|  Thickness           =\n|  Edge                = Milled\n|  Composition         = .917 gold, .083 copper or other metals\n|  Years of Minting    = 2009\u2013present\n|  Mint marks      = Present on some commemorative examples\n|  Obverse             =\n|  Obverse Design      = Reigning British monarch\n|  Obverse Designer    = \n|  Obverse Design Date = \n|  Reverse             = \n|  Reverse Design      = [[Saint George and the Dragon]]\n|  Reverse Designer    = [[Benedetto Pistrucci]]\n|  Reverse Design Date = 1817\n}}\nThe '''Quarter sovereign''' is a commemorative [[British coinage|British coin]] denomination whose introduction was announced by the [[Royal Mint]] in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goldsovereigns.co.uk/quartersovereigns.html|title=Quarter Sovereigns - Available February 2009|website=goldsovereigns.co.uk|access-date=2017-05-30}}</ref> Comprising 2&nbsp;grams of 22 [[Carat (purity)|carat]] or 0.9170 fine gold, the 13.5&nbsp;mm diameter quarter sovereign is the smallest modern [[legal tender]] British [[gold coin]]. It is a quarter of the weight of a [[sovereign (British coin)|sovereign]] with a [[actual gold weight]] (AGW) of 0.05896 troy oz.<ref>https://www.ngccoin.com/price-guide/world/great-britain-1-4-sovereign-km-1117-2009-2014-cuid-1178912-duid-1334169</ref>  {{As of|2019}} it continues to be minted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalmint.com/shop/s/svq17|title=Quarter-Sovereign 2017 {{!}} Gold Sovereigns {{!}} The Royal Mint|website=The Royal Mint|language=en|access-date=2017-05-30}}</ref><ref>https://www.royalmint.com/our-coins/ranges/sovereign/The-Quarter-Sovereign-2019/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British coinage}}\n\n[[Category:Coins of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British gold coins]]\n\n\n{{coin-stub}}\n", "name_user": "EoGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "an average weight", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarter_sovereign"}
{"title_page": "Lonnie Johnson (musician)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Lonnie Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               =  Lonnie Johnson\n| image              = LonnieJohnsonByRussellLee1941Crop.jpg\n| image_size       =\n| landscape         =\n| caption             =Johnson in Chicago, 1941\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Alonzo Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|2|8}}\n| birth_place        =New Orleans, Louisiana, U.S.\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|1970|6|16 |1899|2|8 |mf=yes}}\n| death_place       = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| genre               = Jazz, blues\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Guitar\n| years_active     =\n| label                =[[Okeh Records|Okeh]], [[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]], [[King Records (USA)|King]], [[Bluesville Records|Bluesville]]\n}}\n\n'''Alonzo \"Lonnie\" Johnson''' (February 8, 1899<ref>There is some dispute over the year of his birth; 1894 is given on his passport. Some other sources give 1889.</ref><ref>Big Bill Broonzy remembered that \"Lonnie told me he was born in New Orleans in 1894...\" Source also references 1894 as birth date. Sallis, James (1982). ''The Guitar Players One Instrument and Its Masters in American Music''. p. 33.</ref> \u2013 June 16, 1970) was an American [[blues]] and [[jazz]] singer, guitarist, violinist and songwriter. He was a pioneer of [[jazz guitar]] and [[jazz violin]] and is recognized as the first to play an electrically amplified violin.<ref name=Herzhaft>Herzhaft, G\u00e9rard (1979). ''Encyclopedia of the Blues''.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://delmark.com/delmark.history.htm |title=Delmark History |publisher=Delmark.com |accessdate=30 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606051337/http://delmark.com/delmark.history.htm |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early career===\nJohnson was born in [[New Orleans]], Louisiana, and raised in a family of musicians. He studied violin, piano and guitar as a child and learned to play various other instruments, including the mandolin, but he concentrated on the guitar throughout his professional career. \"There was music all around us,\" he recalled, \"and in my family you'd better play something, even if you just banged on a tin can.\"<ref>Welding, Pete; Byron, Toby, eds. (1991). \"Conversation with Chris Albertson\". ''Bluesland''. Dutton. {{ISBN|0-525-93375-1}}.</ref>\n\nJohnson pioneered the single-string solo guitar styles that have become customary in modern rock, blues and jazz music.\n\nBy his late teens, he was playing guitar and violin in his father's family band at banquets and weddings, alongside his brother James \"Steady Roll\" Johnson.<ref name=cohassey>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608000968/Lonnie-Johnson.html |title=Lonnie Johnson Biography |publisher=Musicianguide.com |date=June 16, 1970 |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> He also worked with the jazz trumpeter [[Punch Miller]] in the [[Storyville, New Orleans|Storyville]] district of New Orleans.\n\nIn 1917, Johnson joined a revue that toured England, returning home in 1919 to find that all of his family, except his brother James, had died in the [[1918 influenza epidemic]].\n\nHe and his brother settled in [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] in 1921,<ref name=manheim>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004726/Lonnie-Johnson.html |title=Lonnie Johnson Biography |publisher=Musicianguide.com |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> where they performed as a duo. Lonnie also worked on [[riverboat]]s and in the orchestras of [[Charlie Creath]] and [[Fate Marable]].\n\nIn 1925 Johnson married, and his wife, Mary, soon began a blues career of her own,<ref name=\"Devil\">{{cite book|title=The Devil's Music|author=Giles Oakley|publisher=[[Da Capo Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/devilsmusichisto00oakl_0/page/162 162/7]|isbn=978-0-306-80743-5|date=1997|url=https://archive.org/details/devilsmusichisto00oakl_0/page/162}}</ref> performing as [[Mary Johnson (singer)|Mary Johnson]] and pursuing a recording career from 1929 to 1936.<ref name=\"Complete\"/> (She is not to be confused with the later [[soul music|soul]] and [[gospel music|gospel]] singer of the same name.) As with many other early blues artists, information on Mary Johnson is often contradictory and confusing. Various online sources give her name before marriage as Mary Smith and state that she began performing in her teens. However, the writer [[James Sallis]]<ref>Sallis, James (1982). ''The Guitar Players''. Bison Books. University of Nebraska.</ref> gave her original name as Mary Williams and stated that her interest in writing and performing blues began when she started helping Lonnie write songs and developed from there. The two never recorded together. They had six children before their divorce in 1932.<ref name=\"Complete\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r250739/review|pure_url=yes}} |title=Mary Johnson, ''Complete Works in Chronological Order, 1929\u20131936'': Review|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n===Success in the 1920s and 1930s===\nIn 1925, Johnson entered and won a blues contest at the Booker T. Washington Theatre in St. Louis, the prize being a recording contract with [[Okeh Records]].<ref name= barlow>Barlow, William (1989). ''\"Looking Up at Down\": The Emergence of Blues Culture''. Temple University Press. pp. 259\u201363. {{ISBN|0-87722-583-4}}.</ref>\nTo his regret, he was then tagged as a blues artist and later found it difficult to be regarded as anything else. He later said, \"I guess I would have done anything to get recorded \u2013 it just happened to be a blues contest, so I sang the blues.\"<ref name=\"manheim\"/> Between 1925 and 1932 he made about 130 recordings for Okeh, many of which sold well (making him one of the most popular OKeh artists). He was called to New York to record with the leading blues singers of the day, including [[Victoria Spivey]] and the [[country blues]] singer [[Alger \"Texas\" Alexander]]. He also toured with [[Bessie Smith]], a top attraction of the [[Theater Owners Bookers Association]].<ref name=barlow/>\n\nIn December 1927, Johnson recorded in Chicago as a guest artist with [[Louis Armstrong and His Hot Five]], paired with the banjoist [[Johnny St. Cyr]]. He played on the sides \"I'm Not Rough\", \"Savoy Blues\", and \"Hotter Than That.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://michaelminn.net/armstrong/index.php?section2 |title=The Louis Armstrong Discography |publisher=Michaelminn.net |accessdate=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902201730/http://michaelminn.net/armstrong/index.php?section2 |archivedate=September 2, 2011  }}</ref> In an unusual move, he was invited to sit in with many OKeh jazz groups. In 1928, he recorded \"Hot and Bothered\", \"Move Over\", and \"The Mooche\" with [[Duke Ellington]] for Okeh.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.depanorama.net/sess.htm |title=A Duke Ellington Panorama |publisher=Depanorama.net |accessdate=30 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017052921/http://www.depanorama.net/sess.htm |archive-date=October 17, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He also recorded with a group called the Chocolate Dandies (in this case, McKinney's Cotton Pickers). He pioneered the guitar solo on the 1927 track \"6/88 Glide\",<ref name=cohassey/> and on many of his early recordings he played [[12-string guitar]] solos in a style that influenced such future jazz guitarists as [[Charlie Christian]] and [[Django Reinhardt]] and gave the instrument new meaning as a jazz voice. He excelled in purely instrumental pieces, some of which he recorded with the white jazz guitarist [[Eddie Lang]], with whom he teamed in 1929. These recordings were among the first to feature black and white musicians performing together, although Lang was credited as Blind Willie Dunn to disguise the fact.<ref name=\"manheim\"/>\n\nMuch of Johnson's music featured experimental improvisations that would now be categorized as jazz rather than blues. According to the blues historian G\u00e9rard Herzhaft,<ref name=\"Herzhaft\"/> Johnson was \"undeniably the creator of the guitar solo played note by note with a pick, which has become the standard in jazz, blues, country, and rock\". Johnson's style reached both the [[Delta blues]]men and urban players who would adapt and develop his one-string solos into the modern electric blues style.<ref name=cohassey/> However, the writer [[Elijah Wald]]<ref>Wald, Elijah (2004). ''Escaping the Delta: Robert Johnson and the Invention of the Blues''. {{ISBN|978-0-06-052427-2}}.</ref> declared that in the 1920s and 1930s Johnson was best known as a sophisticated and urbane singer rather than an instrumentalist: \"Of the forty ads for his records that appeared in the ''[[Chicago Defender]]'' between 1926 and 1931, not one even mentioned that he played guitar.\"\n\nJohnson's compositions often depicted the social conditions confronting urban African Americans (\"Racketeers' Blues\", \"Hard Times Ain't Gone Nowhere\", \"Fine Booze and Heavy Dues\").<ref name=\"Devil\"/> In his lyrics he captured the nuances of male-female love relationships in a way that went beyond [[Tin Pan Alley]] sentimentalism.<ref name=\"Devil\"/> His songs displayed an ability to understand the heartaches of others, which Johnson saw as the essence of his blues.<ref name=barlow/>\n\nAfter touring with [[Bessie Smith]] in 1929, Johnson moved to Chicago and recorded for Okeh with the stride pianist [[James P. Johnson]]. However, with the temporary demise of the recording industry in the [[Great Depression]], he was compelled to make a living outside music, working at one point in a steel mill in [[Peoria, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Devil\"/> In 1932 he moved again, to [[Cleveland]], Ohio, where he lived for the rest of the decade. There he performed on radio programs and intermittently played with the band backing the singer Putney Dandridge.<ref name=cohassey/>\n\nBy the late 1930s, he was recording and performing in Chicago for [[Decca Records]], working with [[Roosevelt Sykes]] and [[Blind John Davis]], among others. In 1939, during a session for [[Bluebird Records]] with the pianist [[Joshua Altheimer]], Johnson used an electric guitar for the first time.<ref name=\"manheim\"/> He recorded 34 tracks for Bluebird over the next five years, including the hits \"He's a Jelly Roll Baker\"<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Russell|year=1997|title=The Blues: From Robert Johnson to Robert Cray|publisher=Carlton Books|location=Dubai|page=13|isbn=1-85868-255-X}}</ref> and \"In Love Again\".<ref name=cohassey/>\n\n===Later career===\n [[File:Lonnie Johnson at my place 1960.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Lonnie Johnson posing with his guitar|Johnson in 1960]]\nAfter World War II, Johnson made the transition to [[rhythm and blues]], recording for [[King Records (USA)|King]] in Cincinnati and having a hit in 1948 with \"[[Tomorrow Night (Coslow and Grosz song)|Tomorrow Night]]\" written by [[Sam Coslow]] and [[Wilhelm Grosz|Will Grosz]]. The topped the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Race Records]] chart for 7 weeks and reached number 19 on the pop chart with sales of three million copies.<ref name=\"manheim\"/> A [[blues ballad]] with piano accompaniment and background singers, the song bore little resemblance to much of Johnson's earlier blues and jazz material. The follow-ups \"Pleasing You\", \"So Tired\", and \"Confused\" were also R&B hits.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]]. ''Top R&B Singles 1942\u20131995''. {{ISBN|0-89820-115-2}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1952 Johnson toured England. Tony Donegan, a British musician who played on the same bill, paid tribute to Johnson by changing his name to [[Lonnie Donegan]]. Johnson's performances are thought to have been received poorly by British audiences; this may have been due to organizational problems with the tour.<ref>{{cite web| title = On a Kind of Vacation: Re-examining African American Blues Musicians' Visits to Britain, 1950\u201358| first = Lawrence| last = Davies| publisher = allthirteenkeys.com| year = 2014| url = http://allthirteenkeys.wordpress.com/2014/06/22/on-a-kind-of-vacation-reexamining-african-american-blues-musicians-visits-to-britain-1950-58/| accessdate = October 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to the United States, Johnson moved to Philadelphia. He worked in a steel foundry and as a janitor. In 1959 he was working at the Benjamin Franklin Hotel in Philadelphia in 1959 when WHAT-FM disc jockey [[Chris Albertson]] located him and produced  ''[[Blues by Lonnie Johnson]]'' for [[Bluesville Records]]. This was followed by other Prestige albums, including one (''[[Blues & Ballads]]'') with the former Ellington boss [[Elmer Snowden]], who had helped Albertson locate Johnson. Snowden had been the original bandleader of the Washingtonians, which Ellington took over after Snowden vacated the position and made into the famous Ellington orchestra. There followed a Chicago engagement for Johnson at the Playboy Club. This succession of events placed him back on the music scene at a fortuitous time: young audiences were embracing folk music, and many veteran performers were stepping out of obscurity. Johnson was reunited with Duke Ellington and appeared as a guest at an all-star folk concert.\n\nIn 1961, Johnson was reunited with his Okeh recording partner Victoria Spivey for another Prestige album, ''Idle Hours'', and the two singers performed at [[Gerdes Folk City]]. In 1963 he toured Europe as part of the [[American Folk Blues Festival]] with [[Muddy Waters]] and others and recorded an album with [[Otis Spann]] in Denmark.\n\nIn May 1965, he performed at a club in Toronto before an audience of four people.<ref name=obit>Campbell, Richard, \"A Legend of Jazz World, Lonnie Johnson Dies\". ''[[Toronto Star]]''. June 17, 1970. p. 50.</ref> Two weeks later, his shows at a different club attracted a larger audience, and Johnson, encouraged by Toronto's relative racial harmony, decided to move to the city. He opened his club, Home of the Blues, on Toronto's [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville Avenue]] in 1966, but it was a business failure, and Johnson was fired by the man who became owner.<ref name=obit/> Through the rest of the decade, he recorded, played clubs in Canada, and embarked on several regional tours.<ref name=cohassey/>\n\nIn March 1969 he was hit by a car while walking on a sidewalk in Toronto.<ref>\"Jazzman Johnson Injured in Crash\". ''[[Toronto Star]]''. March 14, 1969. p. 26.</ref> He was seriously injured, suffering a broken hip and kidney injuries. A benefit concert was held on May 4, 1969, with two dozen acts that included [[Ian and Sylvia]], [[John Lee Hooker]], and [[Hagood Hardy]].<ref>Rubin, Don. \"One of the Best Jazz Shows Ever.\" ''Toronto Star''. May 5, 1969. p. 28.</ref> He never fully recovered from his injuries and suffered what was described as a stroke. He was able to return to the stage for one performance at [[Massey Hall]] on February 23, 1970, walking with the aid of a cane, to sing a couple songs with [[Buddy Guy]]; Johnson received a standing ovation.<ref>McCracken, Melinda. \"Blues Show Turns Them On.\" ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''. February 24, 1970. p. 13.</ref>\n\nJohnson died on June 16, 1970. A funeral was held at [[Mount Hope Catholic Cemetery|Mount Hope Cemetery]] in Toronto by his friends and fellow musicians, but his family members insisted on transferring the body to Philadelphia where he was buried.<ref name=obit/><ref>Miller, Mark (2011). ''Way Down That Lonesome Road: Lonnie Johnson in Toronto 1965\u20131970''. Mercury Press & Teksteditions. pp. 129, 145.</ref> He was \"virtually broke.\"<ref name=obit/> The Killer Blues Headstone project, a nonprofit organization that places headstones on unmarked graves of blues musicians, purchased a headstone for Johnson around 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Non-Profit to Help Bluesman with Unmarked Graves|website=Killer Blues|publisher=Killer Blues Headstone Project. Killerblues.net |url=http://www.killerblues.net/Headstones-Placed.html|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Smithsonian Folkways]] released ''The Complete Folkways Recordings,'' an anthology of Johnson's music, on [[Folkways Records]]. He had been featured on several compilation blues albums from Folkways, beginning in the 1960s, but never released a solo album on the label in his lifetime.\n\nJohnson was posthumously inducted into the [[Louisiana Blues Hall of Fame]] in 1997.\n\n==Influence==\nJohnson's early recordings are the first guitar recordings that display a single-note soloing style with string bending and vibrato. Johnson pioneered this style of guitar playing on records, and his influence is obvious in the playing of [[Django Reinhardt]], [[T-Bone Walker]] and virtually all electric blues guitarists.\n\nOne of [[Elvis Presley]]'s earliest recordings was a version of Johnson's [[blues ballad]] \"Tomorrow Night\", written by Sam Coslow and Will Grosz. Presley's vocal phrasing mimics Johnson's, and many of Presley's signature vibrato and baritone sounds can be heard in development. \"Tomorrow Night\" was also recorded by [[LaVern Baker]] and (in 1957) by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]].\n\nIn the liner notes for the album ''[[Biograph (album)|Biograph]]'', [[Bob Dylan]] described his encounters with Johnson in New York City. \"I was lucky to meet Lonnie Johnson at the same club I was working and I must say he greatly influenced me. You can hear it in that first record. I mean ''Corrina, Corrina''...that's pretty much Lonnie Johnson. I used to watch him every chance I got and sometimes he'd let me play with him. I think he and [[Tampa Red]] and of course [[Scrapper Blackwell]], that's my favorite style of guitar playing.\"<ref>Crowe, Cameron (1985). Liner notes, ''Biograph''. Columbia Records. 10.</ref> In his autobiography, ''[[Chronicles, Vol. 1]]'', Dylan wrote about the performing method he learned from [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]] and remarked that Robert Johnson had learned a lot from Lonnie Johnson. Some of Robert Johnson's songs are seen as new versions of songs recorded by Lonnie Johnson.\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''Lonesome Road'' (King, 1958)\n* ''[[Blues by Lonnie Johnson]]''  (Prestige Bluesville, 1960)\n* ''[[Blues & Ballads]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1960)\n* ''[[Losing Game]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1961)\n* ''[[Idle Hours (album)|Idle Hours]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* ''Another Night to Cry'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* ''Eddie Lang & Lonnie Johnson Vol. 1'' (Swaggie, 1967)\n* ''Eddie Lang & Lonnie Johnson Vol. 2'' (Swaggie, 1970)\n* ''Mr. Trouble'' (Folkways, 1982)\n* ''Tears Don't Fall No More'' (Folkways, 1982)\n* ''Blues, Ballads, and Jumpin' Jazz Vol. 2'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1990)\n* ''The Complete Folkways Recordings'' (Smithsonian Folkways, 1993)\n* ''The Unsung Blues Legend'' (Blues Magnet 2000)\n\n===As sideman===\n* [[Victoria Spivey]], ''Woman Blues]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* Victoria Spivey, ''The Queen and Her Knights'' (Spivey 1965)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of blues musicians]]\n*[[List of jazz musicians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lonnie Johnson}}\n* {{Britannica|305358|Lonnie Johnson}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170608004914/http://redhotjazz.com/ljohnson.html Discography and brief biography]\n*[http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608000968/Lonnie-Johnson.html Biography]\n\n{{Blues|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Lonnie}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Blues musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century violinists]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:American jazz violinists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male violinists]]\n[[Category:Blues revival musicians]]\n[[Category:Country blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz-blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:Louis Armstrong and His Hot Five members]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Gennett Records artists]]\n[[Category:Okeh Records artists]]\n[[Category:Piedmont blues musicians]]\n[[Category:St. Louis blues musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Lonnie Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               =  Lonnie Johnson\n| image              = LonnieJohnsonByRussellLee1941Crop.jpg\n| image_size       =\n| landscape         =\n| caption             =Johnson in Chicago, 1941\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Alonzo Johnson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1899|2|8}}\n| birth_place        =New Orleans, Louisiana, U.S.\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|1970|6|16 |1899|2|8 |mf=yes}}\n| death_place       = Toronto, Ontario, Canada\n| genre               = Jazz, blues\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Guitar\n| years_active     =\n| label                =[[Okeh Records|Okeh]], [[Bluebird Records|Bluebird]], [[King Records (USA)|King]], [[Bluesville Records|Bluesville]]\n}}\n\n'''Alonzo \"Lonnie\" Johnson''' (February 8, 1899<ref>There is some dispute over the year of his birth; 1894 is given on his passport. Some other sources give 1889.</ref><ref>Big Bill Broonzy remembered that \"Lonnie told me he was born in New Orleans in 1894...\" Source also references 1894 as birth date. Sallis, James (1982). ''The Guitar Players One Instrument and Its Masters in American Music''. p. 33.</ref> \u2013 June 16, 1970) was an American [[blues]] and [[jazz]] singer, guitarist, violinist and songwriter. He was a pioneer of [[jazz guitar]] and [[jazz violin]] and is recognized as the first to play an electrically amplified violin.<ref name=Herzhaft>Herzhaft, G\u00e9rard (1979). ''Encyclopedia of the Blues''.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://delmark.com/delmark.history.htm |title=Delmark History |publisher=Delmark.com |accessdate=30 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606051337/http://delmark.com/delmark.history.htm |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early career===\nJohnson was born in [[New Orleans]], Louisiana, and raised in a family of musicians. He studied violin, piano and guitar as a child and learned to play various other instruments, including the mandolin, but he concentrated on the guitar throughout his professional career. \"There was music all around us,\" he recalled, \"and in my family you'd better play something, even if you just banged on a tin can.\"<ref>Welding, Pete; Byron, Toby, eds. (1991). \"Conversation with Chris Albertson\". ''Bluesland''. Dutton. {{ISBN|0-525-93375-1}}.</ref>\n\nJohnson pioneered the single-string solo guitar styles that have become customary in modern rock, blues and jazz music.\n\nBy his late teens, he was playing guitar and violin in his father's family band at banquets and weddings, alongside his brother James \"Steady Roll\" Johnson.<ref name=cohassey>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608000968/Lonnie-Johnson.html |title=Lonnie Johnson Biography |publisher=Musicianguide.com |date=June 16, 1970 |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> He also worked with the jazz trumpeter [[Punch Miller]] in the [[Storyville, New Orleans|Storyville]] district of New Orleans.\n\nIn 1917, Johnson joined a revue that toured England, returning home in 1919 to find that all of his family, except his brother James, had died in the [[1918 influenza epidemic]].\n\nHe and his brother settled in [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] in 1921,<ref name=manheim>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004726/Lonnie-Johnson.html |title=Lonnie Johnson Biography |publisher=Musicianguide.com |accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref> where they performed as a duo. Lonnie also worked on [[riverboat]]s and in the orchestras of [[Charlie Creath]] and [[Fate Marable]].\n\nIn 1925 Johnson married, and his wife, Mary, soon began a blues career of her own,<ref name=\"Devil\">{{cite book|title=The Devil's Music|author=Giles Oakley|publisher=[[Da Capo Press]]|pages=[https://archive.org/details/devilsmusichisto00oakl_0/page/162 162/7]|isbn=978-0-306-80743-5|date=1997|url=https://archive.org/details/devilsmusichisto00oakl_0/page/162}}</ref> performing as [[Mary Johnson (singer)|Mary Johnson]] and pursuing a recording career from 1929 to 1936.<ref name=\"Complete\"/> (She is not to be confused with the later [[soul music|soul]] and [[gospel music|gospel]] singer of the same name.) As with many other early blues artists, information on Mary Johnson is often contradictory and confusing. Various online sources give her name before marriage as Mary Smith and state that she began performing in her teens. However, the writer [[James Sallis]]<ref>Sallis, James (1982). ''The Guitar Players''. Bison Books. University of Nebraska.</ref> gave her original name as Mary Williams and stated that her interest in writing and performing blues began when she started helping Lonnie write songs and developed from there. The two never recorded together. They had six children before their divorce in 1932.<ref name=\"Complete\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r250739/review|pure_url=yes}} |title=Mary Johnson, ''Complete Works in Chronological Order, 1929\u20131936'': Review|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n===Success in the 1920s and 1930s===\nIn 1925, Johnson entered and won a blues contest at the Booker T. Washington Theatre in St. Louis, the prize being a recording contract with [[Okeh Records]].<ref name= barlow>Barlow, William (1989). ''\"Looking Up at Down\": The Emergence of Blues Culture''. Temple University Press. pp. 259\u201363. {{ISBN|0-87722-583-4}}.</ref>\nTo his regret, he was then tagged as a blues artist and later found it difficult to be regarded as anything else. He later said, \"I guess I would have done anything to get recorded \u2013 it just happened to be a blues contest, so I sang the blues.\"<ref name=\"manheim\"/> Between 1925 and 1932 he made about 130 recordings for Okeh, many of which sold well (making him one of the most popular OKeh artists). He was called to New York to record with the leading blues singers of the day, including [[Victoria Spivey]] and the [[country blues]] singer [[Alger \"Texas\" Alexander]]. He also toured with [[Bessie Smith]], a top attraction of the [[Theater Owners Bookers Association]].<ref name=barlow/>\n\nIn December 1927, Johnson recorded in Chicago as a guest artist with [[Louis Armstrong and His Hot Five]], paired with the banjoist [[Johnny St. Cyr]]. He played on the sides \"I'm Not Rough\", \"Savoy Blues\", and \"Hotter Than That.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://michaelminn.net/armstrong/index.php?section2 |title=The Louis Armstrong Discography |publisher=Michaelminn.net |accessdate=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902201730/http://michaelminn.net/armstrong/index.php?section2 |archivedate=September 2, 2011  }}</ref> In an unusual move, he was invited to sit in with many OKeh jazz groups. In 1928, he recorded \"Hot and Bothered\", \"Move Over\", and \"The Mooche\" with [[Duke Ellington]] for Okeh.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.depanorama.net/sess.htm |title=A Duke Ellington Panorama |publisher=Depanorama.net |accessdate=30 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017052921/http://www.depanorama.net/sess.htm |archive-date=October 17, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He also recorded with a group called the Chocolate Dandies (in this case, McKinney's Cotton Pickers). He pioneered the guitar solo on the 1927 track \"6/88 Glide\",<ref name=cohassey/> and on many of his early recordings he played [[12-string guitar]] solos in a style that influenced such future jazz guitarists as [[Charlie Christian]] and [[Django Reinhardt]] and gave the instrument new meaning as a jazz voice. He excelled in purely instrumental pieces, some of which he recorded with the white jazz guitarist [[Eddie Lang]], with whom he teamed in 1929. These recordings were among the first to feature black and white musicians performing together, although Lang was credited as Blind Willie Dunn to disguise the fact.<ref name=\"manheim\"/>\n\nMuch of Johnson's music featured experimental improvisations that would now be categorized as jazz rather than blues. According to the blues historian G\u00e9rard Herzhaft,<ref name=\"Herzhaft\"/> Johnson was \"undeniably the creator of the guitar solo played note by note with a pick, which has become the standard in jazz, blues, country, and rock\". Johnson's style reached both the [[Delta blues]]men and urban players who would adapt and develop his one-string solos into the modern electric blues style.<ref name=cohassey/> However, the writer [[Elijah Wald]]<ref>Wald, Elijah (2004). ''Escaping the Delta: Robert Johnson and the Invention of the Blues''. {{ISBN|978-0-06-052427-2}}.</ref> declared that in the 1920s and 1930s Johnson was best known as a sophisticated and urbane singer rather than an instrumentalist: \"Of the forty ads for his records that appeared in the ''[[Chicago Defender]]'' between 1926 and 1931, not one even mentioned that he played guitar.\"\n\nJohnson's compositions often depicted the social conditions confronting urban African Americans (\"Racketeers' Blues\", \"Hard Times Ain't Gone Nowhere\", \"Fine Booze and Heavy Dues\").<ref name=\"Devil\"/> In his lyrics he captured the nuances of male-female love relationships in a way that went beyond [[Tin Pan Alley]] sentimentalism.<ref name=\"Devil\"/> His songs displayed an ability to understand the heartaches of others, which Johnson saw as the essence of his blues.<ref name=barlow/>\n\nAfter touring with [[Bessie Smith]] in 1929, Johnson moved to Chicago and recorded for Okeh with the stride pianist [[James P. Johnson]]. However, with the temporary demise of the recording industry in the [[Great Depression]], he was compelled to make a living outside music, working at one point in a steel mill in [[Peoria, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Devil\"/> In 1932 he moved again, to [[Cleveland]], Ohio, where he lived for the rest of the decade. There he performed on radio programs and intermittently played with the band backing the singer Putney Dandridge.<ref name=cohassey/>\n\nBy the late 1930s, he was recording and performing in Chicago for [[Decca Records]], working with [[Roosevelt Sykes]] and [[Blind John Davis]], among others. In 1939, during a session for [[Bluebird Records]] with the pianist [[Joshua Altheimer]], Johnson used an electric guitar for the first time.<ref name=\"manheim\"/> He recorded 34 tracks for Bluebird over the next five years, including the hits \"He's a Jelly Roll Baker\"<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite book|first=Tony|last=Russell|year=1997|title=The Blues: From Robert Johnson to Robert Cray|publisher=Carlton Books|location=Dubai|page=13|isbn=1-85868-255-X}}</ref> and \"In Love Again\".<ref name=cohassey/>\n\n===Later career===\n [[File:Lonnie Johnson at my place 1960.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Lonnie Johnson posing with his guitar|Johnson in 1960]]\nAfter World War II, Johnson made the transition to [[rhythm and blues]], recording for [[King Records (USA)|King]] in Cincinnati and having a hit in 1948 with \"[[Tomorrow Night (Coslow and Grosz song)|Tomorrow Night]]\" written by [[Sam Coslow]] and [[Wilhelm Grosz|Will Grosz]]. The topped the ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Race Records]] chart for 7 weeks and reached number 19 on the pop chart with sales of three million copies.<ref name=\"manheim\"/> A [[blues ballad]] with piano accompaniment and background singers, the song bore little resemblance to much of Johnson's earlier blues and jazz material. The follow-ups \"Pleasing You\", \"So Tired\", and \"Confused\" were also R&B hits.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]]. ''Top R&B Singles 1942\u20131995''. {{ISBN|0-89820-115-2}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1952 Johnson toured England. Tony Donegan, a British musician who played on the same bill, paid tribute to Johnson by changing his name to [[Lonnie Donegan]]. Johnson's performances are thought to have been received poorly by British audiences; this may have been due to organizational problems with the tour.<ref>{{cite web| title = On a Kind of Vacation: Re-examining African American Blues Musicians' Visits to Britain, 1950\u201358| first = Lawrence| last = Davies| publisher = allthirteenkeys.com| year = 2014| url = http://allthirteenkeys.wordpress.com/2014/06/22/on-a-kind-of-vacation-reexamining-african-american-blues-musicians-visits-to-britain-1950-58/| accessdate = October 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to the United States, Johnson moved to Philadelphia. He worked in a steel foundry and as a janitor. In 1959 he was working at the Benjamin Franklin Hotel in Philadelphia in 1959 when WHAT-FM disc jockey [[Chris Albertson]] located him and produced  ''[[Blues by Lonnie Johnson]]'' for [[Bluesville Records]]. This was followed by other Prestige albums, including one (''[[Blues & Ballads]]'') with the former Ellington boss [[Elmer Snowden]], who had helped Albertson locate Johnson. Snowden had been the original bandleader of the Washingtonians, which Ellington took over after Snowden vacated the position and made into the famous Ellington orchestra. There followed a Chicago engagement for Johnson at the Playboy Club. This succession of events placed him back on the music scene at a fortuitous time: young audiences were embracing folk music, and many veteran performers were stepping out of obscurity. Johnson was reunited with Duke Ellington and appeared as a guest at an all-star folk concert.\n\nIn 1961, Johnson was reunited with his Okeh recording partner Victoria Spivey for another Prestige album, ''Idle Hours'', and the two singers performed at [[Gerdes Folk City]]. In 1963 he toured Europe as part of the [[American Folk Blues Festival]] with [[Muddy Waters]] and others and recorded an album with [[Otis Spann]] in Denmark.\n\nIn May 1965, he performed at a club in Toronto before an audience of four people.<ref name=obit>Campbell, Richard, \"A Legend of Jazz World, Lonnie Johnson Dies\". ''[[Toronto Star]]''. June 17, 1970. p. 50.</ref> Two weeks later, his shows at a different club attracted a larger audience, and Johnson, encouraged by Toronto's relative racial harmony, decided to move to the city. He opened his club, Home of the Blues, on Toronto's [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville Avenue]] in 1966, but it was a business failure, and Johnson was fired by the man who became owner.<ref name=obit/> Through the rest of the decade, he recorded, played clubs in Canada, and embarked on several regional tours.<ref name=cohassey/>\n\nIn March 1969 he was hit by a car while walking on a sidewalk in Toronto.<ref>\"Jazzman Johnson Injured in Crash\". ''[[Toronto Star]]''. March 14, 1969. p. 26.</ref> He was seriously injured, suffering a broken hip and kidney injuries. A benefit concert was held on May 4, 1969, with two dozen acts that included [[Ian and Sylvia]], [[John Lee Hooker]], and [[Hagood Hardy]].<ref>Rubin, Don. \"One of the Best Jazz Shows Ever.\" ''Toronto Star''. May 5, 1969. p. 28.</ref> He never fully recovered from his injuries and suffered what was described as a stroke. He was able to return to the stage for one performance at [[Massey Hall]] on February 23, 1970, walking with the aid of a cane, to sing a couple songs with [[Buddy Guy]]; Johnson received a standing ovation.<ref>McCracken, Melinda. \"Blues Show Turns Them On.\" ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''. February 24, 1970. p. 13.</ref>\n\nJohnson died on June 16, 1970. A funeral was held at [[Mount Hope Catholic Cemetery|Mount Hope Cemetery]] in Toronto by his friends and fellow musicians, but his family members insisted on transferring the body to Philadelphia where he was buried.<ref name=obit/><ref>Miller, Mark (2011). ''Way Down That Lonesome Road: Lonnie Johnson in Toronto 1965\u20131970''. Mercury Press & Teksteditions. pp. 129, 145.</ref> He was \"virtually broke.\"<ref name=obit/> The Killer Blues Headstone project, a nonprofit organization that places headstones on unmarked graves of blues musicians, purchased a headstone for Johnson around 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Non-Profit to Help Bluesman with Unmarked Graves|website=Killer Blues|publisher=Killer Blues Headstone Project. Killerblues.net |url=http://www.killerblues.net/Headstones-Placed.html|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Smithsonian Folkways]] released ''The Complete Folkways Recordings,'' an anthology of Johnson's music, on [[Folkways Records]]. He had been featured on several compilation blues albums from Folkways, beginning in the 1960s, but never released a solo album on the label in his lifetime.\n\nJohnson was posthumously inducted into the [[Louisiana Blues Hall of Fame]] in 1997.\n\n==Influence==\nJohnson's early recordings are the first guitar recordings that display a single-note soloing style with string bending and vibrato. Johnson pioneered this style of guitar playing on records, and his influence is obvious in the playing of [[Django Reinhardt]], [[T-Bone Walker]] and virtually all electric blues guitarists.\n\nOne of [[Elvis Presley]]'s earliest recordings was a version of Johnson's [[blues ballad]] \"Tomorrow Night\", written by Sam Coslow and Will Grosz. Presley's vocal phrasing mimics Johnson's, and many of Presley's signature vibrato and baritone sounds can be heard in development. \"Tomorrow Night\" was also recorded by [[LaVern Baker]] and (in 1957) by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]].\n\nIn the liner notes for the album ''[[Biograph (album)|Biograph]]'', [[Bob Dylan]] described his encounters with Johnson in New York City. \"I was lucky to meet Lonnie Johnson at the same club I was working and I must say he greatly influenced me. You can hear it in that first record. I mean ''Corrina, Corrina''...that's pretty much Lonnie Johnson. I used to watch him every chance I got and sometimes he'd let me play with him. I think he and [[Tampa Red]] and of course [[Scrapper Blackwell]], that's my favorite style of guitar playing.\"<ref>Crowe, Cameron (1985). Liner notes, ''Biograph''. Columbia Records. 10.</ref> In his autobiography, ''[[Chronicles, Vol. 1]]'', Dylan wrote about the performing method he learned from [[Robert Johnson (musician)|Robert Johnson]] and remarked that Robert Johnson had learned a lot from Lonnie Johnson. Some of Robert Johnson's songs are seen as new versions of songs recorded by Lonnie Johnson.\n\n==Discography==\n===As leader===\n* ''Lonesome Road'' (King, 1958)\n* ''[[Blues by Lonnie Johnson]]''  (Prestige Bluesville, 1960)\n* ''[[Blues & Ballads]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1960)\n* ''[[Losing Game]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1961)\n* ''[[Idle Hours (album)|Idle Hours]]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* ''Another Night to Cry'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* ''Eddie Lang & Lonnie Johnson Vol. 1'' (Swaggie, 1967)\n* ''Eddie Lang & Lonnie Johnson Vol. 2'' (Swaggie, 1970)\n* ''Mr. Trouble'' (Folkways, 1982)\n* ''Tears Don't Fall No More'' (Folkways, 1982)\n* ''Blues, Ballads, and Jumpin' Jazz Vol. 2'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1990)\n* ''The Complete Folkways Recordings'' (Smithsonian Folkways, 1993)\n* ''The Unsung Blues Legend'' (Blues Magnet 2000)\n\n===As sideman===\n* [[Victoria Spivey]], ''Woman Blues]'' (Prestige Bluesville, 1962)\n* Victoria Spivey, ''The Queen and Her Knights'' (Spivey 1965)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of blues musicians]]\n*[[List of jazz musicians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lonnie Johnson}}\n* {{Britannica|305358|Lonnie Johnson}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20170608004914/http://redhotjazz.com/ljohnson.html Discography and brief biography]\n*[http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608000968/Lonnie-Johnson.html Biography]\n\n{{Blues|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Lonnie}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century violinists]]\n[[Category:African-American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n[[Category:American jazz violinists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Blues musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Blues revival musicians]]\n[[Category:Country blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Gennett Records artists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Jazz-blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male violinists]]\n[[Category:Okeh Records artists]]\n[[Category:Piedmont blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:St. Louis blues musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Louis Armstrong and His Hot Five members]]\n", "name_user": "Vmavanti", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lonnie_Johnson_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Keerthy Suresh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actress}}\n{{Indian name|Keerthy|Suresh}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Keerthy Suresh\n| image              = Keerthy Suresh at Sandakozhi 2 Press Meet.png\n| caption            = Keerthy at Press Meet\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|10|17|df=y}}<ref name=\"indianexpress\">{{cite news|title=Happy Birthday Keerthy Suresh|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/keerthy-suresh-thaanaa-serndha-koottam-suriya-nex-film-heroine-3087223|accessdate=17 October 2016|newspaper=Indian Express India|date=17 October 2016|quote=The actor, who turned 24 on Monday, is the new favourite of Kollywood filmmakers.}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Thiruvananthapuram]], [[Kerala]], India<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://highlightsindia.com/keerthy-suresh-early-life-and-personal-details-career-and-net-worth/ |title = Keerthy Suresh-Early Life and Personal Details, Career and Net Worth|date = 14 February 2018}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years active       = 2000\u20132005<br>2013\u2013present\n| parents             = {{ubl|G. Suresh Kumar|[[Menaka (actress)|Menaka]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Keerthy Suresh''' (born 17 October 1992) is an Indian film actress who appears predominantly in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]] and [[Malayalam]] films. She won the [[National Film Award for Best Actress]] for portraying actress [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] in the biopic ''[[Mahanati]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmibeat.com/malayalam/news/2014/characters-scope-to-perform-excites-me-says-keerthi-menaka-145418.html|title=Characters Which Has Scope To Perform Excites Me, Says Keerthi Menaka|work=www.filmibeat.com|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nKeerthy is the daughter of producer Suresh Kumar and actress [[Menaka (actress)|Menaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2013/may/13/Menaka-was-treated-like-a-queen-476820.html|title=Menaka was treated like a queen|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> Keerthy began acting as a child actress in the early 2000s and returned to films after studying fashion design. She had her first lead role in the 2013 [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Geethaanjali]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/siima-2014-malayalam-drishyam-gets-best-film-award-dileep-bags-best-actor-award-winners-list-609100|title=SIIMA 2014 Malayalam: 'Drishyam' Gets Best Film Award; Dileep Bags Best Actor Award &#91;Winners' List&#93;|date=15 September 2014}}</ref> She went on to star in films  such as ''[[Ring Master]]'' (2014), ''[[Idhu Enna Maayam]]'' (2015), ''[[Rajini Murugan]]'' (2016), ''[[Remo_(film)|Remo]]'' (2016), ''[[Nenu Sailaja]]'' (2016), ''[[Bairavaa]]'' (2017), ''[[Nenu Local]]'' (2017), ''[[Thaana Serndha Kootam]]'' (2018), ''[[Mahanati]]'' (2018), ''[[Sandakozhi 2]]'' (2018) and ''[[Sarkar (2018 film)|Sarkar]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nKeerthy was born to [[Malayalam]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eenadu.net/magazines/sunday-magazine/sunday-magazineinner.aspx?catfullstory=10448|title=\u0c38\u0c3f\u0c28\u0c3f\u0c2e\u0c3e \u0c15\u0c37\u0c4d\u0c1f\u0c3e\u0c32\u0c47\u0c35\u0c40 \u0c32\u0c47\u0c35\u0c41...!|website=www.eenadu.net|access-date=5 February 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217081956/http://www.eenadu.net/magazines/sunday-magazine/sunday-magazineinner.aspx?catfullstory=10448|archivedate=17 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> film producer and director Suresh Kumar and [[Tamils|Tamil]] actress [[Menaka (actress)|Menaka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/Menaka-was-treated-like-a-queen/2013/05/13/article1587175.ece|title=Menaka was treated like a queen|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://malayalam.oneindia.in/movies/news/want-to-play-memorable-roles-like-mom-keerthy-20140613141152-122280.html|title=Want to play memorable roles like mom|work=malayalam.filmibeat.com|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=13 June 2014}}</ref> She has an elder sister Revathy Suresh. Until class four, Keerthy did her schooling in [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref name=NIE>{{cite news|last1=Gupta|first1=Rinku|title=Mayas Role Is Very Close to My Heart|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Mayas-Role-Is-Very-Close-to-My-Heart/2015/04/07/article2750813.ece|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=7 April 2015|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref> She then studied in [[Kendriya Vidyalaya]], [[Pattom]], [[Thiruvananthapuram]] before coming back to Chennai to join the [[Pearl Academy]], where she completed her degree in [[fashion design]].<ref name=\"One for the family\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-for-the-family/article4951420.ece|title=One for the family|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=18 November 2014|date=25 July 2013|last1=Sathyendran|first1=Nita}}</ref> She also spent time on an exchange program in [[Scotland]] for four months, before completing a two-month internship in London. Despite making a career in acting, she has stated that she was also \"seriously considering a career in designing\".<ref name=\"Menaka was treated like a queen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/Menaka-was-treated-like-a-queen/2013/05/13/article1587175.ece|title=Menaka was treated like a queen|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=StarsFact|title=Keerthy Suresh| work=Keerthy Suresh Height, Weight, Age, Affairs, Wiki & Facts|date=10 November 2016|url=https://starsfact.com/keerthy-suresh/|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn the early 2000s, Keerthy worked as a child actress in a few of her father's productions, such as ''[[Pilots (film)|Pilots]]'' (2000), ''[[Achaneyanenikkishtam]]'' (2001) and ''[[Kuberan (2002 film)|Kuberan]]'' (2002) and some television serials.<ref name=\"One for the family\"/> 11 years after ''Kuberan'', she made her debut as a lead actress in [[Priyadarshan]]'s horror film ''[[Geethaanjali]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/nishan-to-romance-keerthi/74495/story.htm|title=Nishan to romance Keerthi|date=15 July 2013|work=Nowrunning|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> in which she had a [[dual role]]. She was still studying during that time and shot for ''Geethanjali'' during her semester break.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/A-star-is-born/2013/11/14/article1875959.ece|title=A star is born|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> Reviews on the film and her performance were mixed, with Sify writing that she \"does put in some effort but makes only a limited impression in a double role\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/geethanjali-review-malayalam-15043242.html|title=Movie Review : Geethanjali|work=Sify|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> while Rediff wrote that she \"has got a plum role but whether she impresses with her acting prowess is another matter\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-geethanjali-disappoints/20131115.htm |title=Review: Geethanjali disappoints |date=15 November 2013 |work=Rediff |accessdate=18 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129045722/http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-geethanjali-disappoints/20131115.htm |archivedate=29 November 2014 |df= }}</ref> In 2014, Keerthy had her next release ''[[Ring Master]]'', directed by Rafi of [[Rafi Mecartin]] duo, in which she shared screen space with [[Dileep (actor)|Dileep]]. She played a blind girl,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news-and-interviews/Playing-a-blind-girl-is-not-an-easy-task-Keerthy-Suresh/articleshow/33651802.cms|title= Playing a blind girl is not an easy task: Keerthy Suresh|work=The Times of India|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> which she said was much more challenging than her double role in ''Geethanjali''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140412/entertainment-mollywood/article/keerthy-suresh-%E2%80%98blind%E2%80%99-date|title=Keerthy Suresh on a 'blind' date|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> The film was a commercial success,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/six-months-six-months-malayalam-news-109844|title=Six months, six months|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/Screening-the-Past/2014/07/01/article2308439.ece|title=Screening the Past|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> being termed a \"super hit\" by [[Sify]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/boxoffice.php?id=15057846&cid=14625530|title=Kerala Box-Office April 10 to June 15 Summer Hits|publisher=Sify|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Keerthy accepted her first projects outside of Malayalam and signed on to appear in several Tamil film projects simultaneously. Her first film release was [[A. L. Vijay]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Idhu Enna Maayam]]'' (2015), opposite [[Vikram Prabhu]], though the film did not perform well at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/The-shooting-of-my-first-Tamil-film-is-going-on-Keerthy-Suresh/articleshow/44847371.cms|title=The shooting of my first Tamil film is going on: Keerthy Suresh|work=The Times of India|date=17 October 2014}}</ref> Her busy schedule throughout 2015 meant that she had to opt out of films which she had already started working on, including [[N. Krishna|Krishna]]'s ''[[Maane Thaene Paeye]]'' and Deekay's ''[[Kavalai Vendam]]'', in order to accommodate bigger projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Keerthi-Suresh-is-Aaris-pair-in-Krishnas-rom-com/articleshow/41005433.cms|title=Keerthi Suresh is Aari's pair in Krishna's rom-com|work=The Times of India|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> She consequently worked on two films with [[Sivakarthikeyan]] in quick succession, ''[[Rajini Murugan]]'' and ''[[Remo (film)|Remo]]'', while also playing the lead role in [[Prabhu Solomon]]'s ''[[Thodari]]'', alongside [[Dhanush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Anushka-Shetty-wishes-Keerthy-Suresh-luck-in-Kwood/articleshow/44917200.cms|title=Anushka Shetty wishes Keerthy Suresh luck in K'wood|work=The Times of India|accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> Her Telugu debut was the 2016 film [[Nenu Sailaja]] with actor [[Ram Pothineni]]. In January 2017, Keerthy appeared in ''[[Bairavaa]]'', opposite actor [[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]] and directed by Bharathan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/bairavaa-bhairava-3-weeks-box-office-collection-vijays-film-earns-around-rs-110-crore-22-days-714810 | title=Bairavaa (Bhairava) 3 weeks box office collection: Vijay's film earns around Rs 110 crore in 22 days | accessdate=15 February 2017 | work=IB Times | date=4 February 2017}}</ref> She also appeared in Tamil film ''[[Paambhu Sattai]]'' and Telugu film ''[[Nenu Local]]'' in 2017.\n\nIn early 2018, she appeared in ''[[Agnyaathavaasi]]'' and ''[[Thaana Serndha Kootam]]''. She also acted in [[Nag Ashwin]]'s Telugu-Tamil bilingual epic ''[[Mahanati]]'' where she portrayed the late southern actress [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]] and for which her performance has received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/mahanati-actor-keerthy-suresh-on-playing-savirtri-im-glad-i-convinced-her-daughter-with-my-portrayal-4465101.html|title=Mahanati actor Keerthy Suresh on playing Savirtri: I'm glad I convinced her daughter with my portrayal- Entertainment News, Firstpost|publisher=|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref> Her recently released movies include ''[[Saamy 2]]'', The Sequel of ''[[Saamy]]'', opposite [[Vikram (actor)|Vikram]], ''[[Sandakozhi 2]]'' opposite [[Vishal (actor)|Vishal]], and ''[[Sarkar (2018 film)|Sarkar]]'' starring [[Vijay(actor)|Vijay]], directed by [[AR Murugadoss]].\n\nAs of 2019, she has signed on to appear in multiple projects such as the [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Marakkar: Arabikadalinte Simham]]'' directed by [[Priyadarshan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/kalyani-priyadarshan-confirms-working-keerthy-suresh-mohanlal-film-90276%3famp|title=Kalyani Priyadarshan confirms working with Keerthy Suresh for Mohanlal film|date=20 October 2018}}</ref> a yet to be titled [[Telugu language|Telugu]] film under the director Narendra Nath. She has a cameo appearance in the [[Nagarjuna]] starrer ''[[Manmadhudu 2]]'', which is directed by [[Rahul Ravindran]]. She is also set to make her [[Bollywood]] debut in ''[[Maidaan]]'' opposite [[Ajay Devgn]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"3\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"3\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 97%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Role(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Language(s)\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Tooltip|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Pilots (film)|Pilots]]'' || Herself  || [[Rajiv Anchal]] || rowspan=\"6\"|[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] || rowspan=\"3\"|Child artist ||\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Achaneyanenikkishtam]]'' || Unnamed || Suresh Krishnan ||\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Kuberan (2002 film)|Kuberan]]'' || Siddharth's adopte