oxes\n| title = Awards for ''The Crown''\n| list =\n{{GoldenGlobeTVDrama}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Drama Television Series}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n}}\n{{Peter Morgan}}\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crown, The}}\n[[Category:The Crown (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American political drama television series]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Series Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:British political drama television series]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Winston Churchill]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George VI]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Gamal Abdel Nasser]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John Profumo]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Left Bank Pictures]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British\u2013American television drama series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}  \n{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n |show_name = The Crown\n |image = The Crown Title Card.jpg\n |genre = Historical drama\n |creator = [[Peter Morgan]]\n |starring = {{Plainlist|\n<!--Order of the cast is determined by the order that is given during the opening credits of the first episodes, per the MOS! New cast additions will be made based on when first credited. -->\n* [[Claire Foy]]\n* [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]]\n* [[Vanessa Kirby]]\n* [[Eileen Atkins]]\n* [[Jeremy Northam]]\n* [[Victoria Hamilton]]\n* [[Ben Miles]]\n* [[Greg Wise]]\n* [[Jared Harris]]\n* [[John Lithgow]]\n* [[Alex Jennings]]\n* [[Lia Williams]]\n* [[Anton Lesser]]\n* [[Matthew Goode]]\n* [[Olivia Colman]]\n* [[Tobias Menzies]]\n* [[Helena Bonham Carter]]\n* [[Ben Daniels]]\n* [[Jason Watkins (actor)|Jason Watkins]]\n* [[Marion Bailey]]\n* [[Erin Doherty]]\n* [[Jane Lapotaire]]\n* [[Charles Dance]]\n* [[Josh O'Connor]]\n* [[Geraldine Chaplin]]\n* [[Michael Maloney]]\n* [[Emerald Fennell]]\n* [[Andrew Buchan]]\n}}\n |theme_music_composer = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n |composer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rupert Gregson-Williams]] {{small|(s. 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Lorne Balfe]] {{small|(s. 2)}}\n* [[Martin Phipps]] {{small|(s. 3)}}\n}}\n |country = {{Plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-27539739 |title=Netflix plans original UK drama about the Queen |date=23 May 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n* United States<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2016/10/15/the-crown-claire-foy-and-matt-smith-on-the-making-of-the-100m-ne/ |title=The Crown: Claire Foy and Matt Smith on the making of the \u00a3100m Netflix series |first=Mick |last=Brown |date=3 November 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n |language = English\n |num_seasons = 3\n |num_episodes = 30\n |list_episodes = #Episodes\n |executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Morgan\n* [[Stephen Daldry]]\n* [[Andy Harries]]\n* [[Philip Martin (director)|Philip Martin]]\n* Suzanne Mackie\n* Matthew Byam-Shaw\n* Robert Fox\n* [[Tanya Seghatchian]]\n* Nina Wolarsky\n* Allie Goss\n}}\n |producer = [[Andrew Eaton]]\n |location = United Kingdom\n |runtime = 47\u201361 minutes\n |company = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Left Bank Pictures]]\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n}}\n |distributor = [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n |network = [[Netflix]]\n |picture_format = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])<ref>{{cite web |title=The Crown |url=http://realorfake4k.com/my-product/the-crown/ |website=Real or Fake 4K |accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>\n |first_aired = {{Start date|2016|11|4}}\n |last_aired = {{End date|present}}\n}}\n'''''The Crown''''' is a<!--Please do not add any countries here per WP:TVLEAD as the series is both a British and American production. See the talk page for more.--> historical drama [[web television]] series about the reign of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], created and principally written by [[Peter Morgan]], and produced by [[Left Bank Pictures]] and [[Sony Pictures Television]] for [[Netflix]]. It grew out of Morgan's film ''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'' (2006) and his stage play ''[[The Audience (2013 play)|The Audience]]'' (2013), and is credited as based on the latter. The first season covers the period from Queen Elizabeth and [[Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]'s marriage in 1947 to the disintegration of her sister [[Princess Margaret]]'s engagement to Group Captain [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] in 1955. The second season covers the period from the [[Suez Crisis]] in 1956 to the retirement of Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] in 1963 and the birth of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]] in 1964. The third season spans the period between 1964 and 1977, including [[Harold Wilson]]'s two periods as prime minister, and introduces [[Camilla Shand]].  The fourth will include [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s premiership and introduce [[Lady Diana Spencer]].<!--Per WP:CITELEAD, references are not required in the lead if the information and references are already included in the body!--> The fifth and final season will cover the Queen's reign into the 21st century.\n\nThe series covers Elizabeth's life from her younger years to her reign in the 21st century, and with new actors being cast every two seasons. [[Claire Foy]] portrays the Queen in the first two seasons, alongside [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] as Prince Philip and [[Vanessa Kirby]] as Princess Margaret. For the third and fourth seasons, [[Olivia Colman]] takes over as the Queen, [[Tobias Menzies]] as Prince Philip, and [[Helena Bonham Carter]] as Princess Margaret. [[Imelda Staunton]] will succeed Colman for the fifth and final season. Filming for the series takes place at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]] in [[Borehamwood]], Hertfordshire, with location shooting throughout the United Kingdom and internationally. The first season was released on Netflix on November 4, 2016, the second on December 8, 2017, and the third on November 17, 2019. Although originally intended to last sixty episodes over six seasons, the series has been renewed for only two further seasons, taking it to an eventual total of five.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/why-netflix-is-ending-crown-at-season-5-1276147|title=Why 'The Crown' Is Ending With Season 5 on Netflix|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Davies|first=Caroline|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/jan/31/the-crown-final-season-five-imelda-staunton-the-queen|title=The Crown will end after season five, with Imelda Staunton as Queen|date=2020-01-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n''The Crown'' has been praised for its writing, acting, directing, cinematography, production values, and relatively accurate historical account of Queen Elizabeth's reign. It received accolades at the [[23rd Screen Actors Guild Awards]], won Best Actress for Foy in the lead role and Best Actor for [[John Lithgow]] as [[Winston Churchill]], and secured a total of 26 nominations for its first two seasons at the [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, including twice for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/crown|title=The Crown| website= Television Academy|language=en|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The series was nominated for Best Drama TV Series at the [[77th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/crown|title=Crown, The|website=www.goldenglobes.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Premise==\n''The Crown'' traces the life of Queen [[Elizabeth II]] from [[Wedding of Princess Elizabeth and Philip Mountbatten|her wedding]] in 1947, to Philip Mountbatten,<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite news |last=Singh |first=Anita |date=August 19, 2015 |title=\u00a3100m Netflix Series Recreates Royal Wedding |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/11813152/100m-Netflix-series-recreates-royal-wedding.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322133559/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/11813152/100m-Netflix-series-recreates-royal-wedding.html |archivedate=22 March 2016 |accessdate=18 November 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> until the early 21st century.<ref name=\"FinalSeasonAnnounce\" /> [[Claire Foy]] portrays Elizabeth in seasons one and two,<ref name=\"FoyCast\" /> and [[Olivia Colman]] in seasons three and four.<ref name=\"ColmanCast\" /> Foy is set for a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in a flashback scene in the fourth season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/tv/claire-foy-will-return-as-queen-elizabeth-in-the-crowns-fourth-season/ |first=Caroline |last=Hallemann |title=Claire Foy Will Return as Queen Elizabeth in The Crown's Fourth Season |website=Town and Country |date=27 November 2019 |accessdate=27 November 2019}}</ref> [[Imelda Staunton]] will portray the Queen in the fifth and final season.<ref name=\"FinalSeasonAnnounce\" />\n\nThe first season depicts events up to 1955, with [[Winston Churchill]] resigning as prime minister and the Queen's sister [[Princess Margaret]] deciding not to marry [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/742509/the-crown-netflix-timeline-what-year-series-1-finish-season-2-what-will-happen-when|title=The Crown: What year did Series 1 finish? What will be in season 2?|last=Smith|first=Russ|website=Daily Express|date=13 December 2016|accessdate=24 January 2018}}</ref> The second season covers the [[Suez Crisis]] in 1956 leading to the retirement of Prime Minister [[Anthony Eden]], the retirement of Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]] in 1963 following the [[Profumo affair]] political scandal, and the birth of [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]] in 1964.<ref name= \"GoodeCast\" /><ref name=\"KennedysCast\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/the-crown-cast-michael-c-hall-jodi-balfour-kennedy-matthew-goode-netflix-1201906364/ |title='The Crown' Adds Michael C Hall & Jodi Balfour As Jack & Jackie Kennedy |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |website= Deadline Hollywood |date=9 February 2017 |accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BettanyTalks\" /> The third season covers 1964 to 1977, beginning with [[Harold Wilson]]'s election as prime minister and ending with her [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Silver Jubilee]],<ref>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crown-review-1251712|title='The Crown' Season 3: TV Review| last=Fienberg| first=Daniel| magazine= [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=6 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105130150/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/crown-review-1251712|archive-date=5 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> also covering [[Edward Heath]]'s time as prime minister.<ref name=\"meet-the-cast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-11-17/meet-the-cast-of-the-crown-season-3/2/|title=Meet the cast of The Crown season 3|website=[[RadioTimes]]|date=17 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref> The third season also introduces [[Camilla Shand]].<ref name=\"meet-the-cast\" /> The fourth season will be set during [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s premiership and will feature [[Lady Diana Spencer]], and introduce [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex|Prince Harry]].<ref name=\"THRSeason3&4\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a30993984/prince-william-the-crown-season-4/ |first=Megan |last=Sutton |title=First look pictures show young Prince William in The Crown season 4 |website=Good Housekeeping |date=19 February 2020 |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref> The fifth season will cover the Queen's reign into the early years of the 21st century.<ref name=\"FinalSeasonAnnounce\" />\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|List of The Crown characters}}\n===Main===\n<!--Order of the cast is determined by the order that is given during the opening credits of the first episodes, per the MOS, with new additions to the opening credits appended to the list-->\n* [[Claire Foy]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Olivia Colman]] (season 3) as [[Queen Elizabeth II]]<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Tobias Menzies]] (season 3) as [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[Vanessa Kirby]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Helena Bonham Carter]] (season 3) as [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]]<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[Eileen Atkins]] as [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] (season 1)<ref name=\"geeksofdoom\" />\n* [[Jeremy Northam]] as [[Anthony Eden]] (seasons 1\u20132)<ref name=\"finalreel\" />\n* [[Victoria Hamilton]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Marion Bailey]] (season 3) as [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]]<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[Ben Miles]] as Group Captain [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] (season 1, featured season 2)<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/aug/21/different-kind-of-royal-fever-victoria-the-crown-jenna-coleman |title=Why Britain's psyche is gripped by a different kind of royal fever |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Vanessa |last=Thorpe |date=21 August 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Greg Wise]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Charles Dance]] (season 3) as [[Louis, Earl Mountbatten of Burma]]\n* [[Jared Harris]] as [[King George VI]] (season 1, featured season 2)<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[John Lithgow]] as [[Winston Churchill]] (season 1, featured seasons 2\u20133)<ref name=\"telegraph\" />\n* [[Alex Jennings]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Derek Jacobi]] (featured season 3) as [[Prince Edward, Duke of Windsor]]<ref name=\"CastComparisons\" />\n* [[Lia Williams]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Geraldine Chaplin]] (season 3) as [[Wallis, Duchess of Windsor]]<ref name=\"CastComparisons\" />\n* [[Anton Lesser]] as [[Harold Macmillan]] (season 2)<ref name=\"LesserCast\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/ng-interactive/2016/nov/01/filming-the-crown-on-the-set-of-the-netflix-blockbuster-in-pictures |first=Sarah |last=Lee |title=Filming The Crown: on the set of the lavish Netflix series \u2013 in pictures |newspaper=The Guardian |date=1 November 2016 |accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Matthew Goode]] (season 2) and [[Ben Daniels]] (season 3) as [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, Earl of Snowdon]]<ref name=\"GoodeCast\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/downton-abbey/news/a819685/downton-abbey-matthew-goode-joins-netflix-the-crown-lord-snowdon/ |title=Downton Abbey's Matthew Goode is joining the cast of Netflix's The Crown |website=Digital Spy |first=Ian |last=Sandwell |date=January 23, 2017 |accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jason Watkins (actor)|Jason Watkins]] as [[Harold Wilson]] (season 3)<ref name=\"CarterConfirm\" />\n* [[Erin Doherty]] as [[Princess Anne]] (season 3)\n* [[Jane Lapotaire]] as [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]] (season 3)<!-- 101 105 202 209 -->\n* [[Josh O'Connor]] as [[Charles, Prince of Wales]] (season 3)\n* [[Michael Maloney]] as [[Edward Heath]] (season 3)\n* [[Emerald Fennell]] as [[Camilla Shand]] (season 3)\n* [[Andrew Buchan]] as [[Andrew Parker Bowles]] (season 3)\n\n====Featured====\nThe following actors are credited in the opening titles of single episodes in which they play a significant role.\n* [[Stephen Dillane]] as [[Graham Sutherland]], a noted artist who paints a portrait of the ageing Churchill (season 1)\n* [[Gemma Whelan]] as Patricia Campbell, a secretary who works with Lord Altrincham and types up his editorial (season 2)\n* [[John Heffernan (actor)|John Heffernan]] as [[John Grigg (writer)|Lord Altrincham]], a writer who penned a scathing criticism of the Queen (season 2)\n* [[Paul Sparks]] as [[Billy Graham]], a prominent American preacher with whom Elizabeth consults (season 2)<ref name=\"CastComparisons\" />\n* [[Michael C. Hall]] as [[John F. Kennedy]], the [[List of presidents of the United States|35th]] [[President of the United States]] who visits the Queen (season 2)\n* [[Jodi Balfour]] as [[Jacqueline Kennedy]], the [[First Lady of the United States]] (season 2)\n* [[Burghart Klau\u00dfner]] as Dr. [[Kurt Hahn]], the founder of [[Gordonstoun]], where Philip and Charles went to school (season 2)\n* Finn Elliot as school-aged Prince Philip (season 2, guest season 3)<ref name=\"CastComparisons\" />\n* Julian Baring as school-aged Prince Charles (season 2)<ref name=\"CastComparisons\">{{cite web|url=https://the-crown-netflix.com/2017/12/11/the-crown-season-two-representation-vs-reality/|title=The Crown Season Two: Representation vs Reality|publisher=Netflix|date=11 December 2017|accessdate= 2 January 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Clancy Brown]] as [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], [[List of presidents of the United States|36th]] [[President of the United States]] (season 3)\n* [[Mark Lewis Jones]] as [[Edward Millward]] (season 3)\n* [[Tim McMullan]] as [[Robin Woods]] (season 3)\n* [[Harry Treadaway]] as [[Roddy Llewellyn]] (season 3)\n\n===Recurring===\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}<!-- List of NAMED characters recurring across multiple seasons. -->\n* Billy Jenkins as young Prince Charles (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 103 105 107 108 110 201 202 203 -->\n* Grace and Amelia Gilmour as young Princess Anne (seasons 1\u20132, uncredited)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lacey|first=Robert|date=October 5, 2017|title=The Crown: The Inside History|url=https://www.blinkpublishing.co.uk/the-crown.html|location=London|publisher=[[Blink Publishing]]|page=354|isbn=9781911274988|author-link=}}</ref>\n* [[Clive Francis]] as [[Robert Gascoyne-Cecil, 5th Marquess of Salisbury|Lord Salisbury]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 102 103 104 105 107 109 201 203 206 -->\n* [[Pip Torrens]] as [[Alan Lascelles|Tommy Lascelles]] (seasons 1\u20132; guest season 3)<!-- 101 102 103 104 105 106 107 108 110 201 202 203 204 205 206 207 302 -->\n* [[Harry Hadden-Paton]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Charles Edwards (English actor)|Charles Edwards]] (season 3) as [[Martin Charteris, Baron Charteris of Amisfield|Martin Charteris]]<!-- 101 102 103 106 107 108 201 202 203 205 208 301 302 303 304 307 308 309 310 -->\n* [[Daniel Ings]] as [[Michael Parker (courtier)|Mike Parker]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 103 105 106 108 109 201 202 203 -->\n* Lizzy McInnerny as Margaret \"Bobo\" MacDonald (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 102 103 105 106 108 109 110 201 203 204 207 208-->\n* Michael Bertenshaw as the [[Piers Legh|Master of the Household]] (season 2; guest season 1)<!-- 101 201 208 -->\n* [[Patrick Ryecart]] as the [[Bernard Fitzalan-Howard, 16th Duke of Norfolk|Duke of Norfolk]] (seasons 1, 3; guest season 2)<!-- 101 103 105 203 306 310 -->\n* [[Will Keen]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[David Rintoul]] (season 3) as [[Michael Adeane]]<ref name=\"RadioTimesCastPage2\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-11-04/meet-the-cast-of-the-crown-season-3/2/|title=Meet the cast of The Crown season 3|last=Bley Griffiths|first=Eleanor|magazine=[[Radio Times]]|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=10 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110050658/https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-11-04/meet-the-cast-of-the-crown-season-3/2/|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><!-- 101 106 107 108 109 110 201 202 203 204 205 206 207 208 210 301, 302, 303, 304, 305, 306, 307, 310 -->\n* [[James Laurenson]] as [[John Weir (physician)|Doctor Weir]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 102 104 207 210 -->\n* [[Mark Tandy (actor)|Mark Tandy]] as [[Cecil Beaton]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 101 110 203 204 206 210 -->\n* [[Rosalind Knight]] (season 1) and [[Sophie Leigh Stone]] (season 2) as [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]], Philip's mother \n* Andy Sanderson (season 1) and [[Michael Thomas (actor)|Michael Thomas]] (season 3) as [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]], Elizabeth's uncle<ref name=\"geeksofdoom\">{{cite web |url=http://www.geeksofdoom.com/2016/01/06/trailers-netflix-the-crown-the-get-down |title=Trailers for Netflix series 'The Crown,' and 'The Get Down' |website=Geeks of Doom |date=6 January 2016 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> (seasons 1, 3)<!-- 101 102 103 105 107 108 301, 302, 304, 305, 307, 310-->\n* [[Michael Culkin]] as [[Rab Butler]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 102 104 109 201 203 207 -->\n* George Asprey as [[Walter Monckton]] (seasons 1\u20132)<!-- 102 103 104 201 203 206 -->\n* Verity Russell as young Princess Elizabeth (season 1; guest season 3)<!-- 103 105 107 110 302 -->\n* Beau Gadsdon as young Princess Margaret (season 1; guest season 3)<!-- 103 107 110 302 -->\n* [[James Hillier (actor)|James Hillier]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Sam Phillips (actor)|Sam Phillips]] (season 3) as the Queen's [[equerry]] <!-- 104 105 107 108 109 110 203 205 206 207 208 209 210 301 302 303 305 306 307 308 309-->\n* [[Anna Madeley]] as [[Clarissa Eden]] (season 1; guest season 2)<!-- 105 109 110 203 -->\n* Nick Hendrix (season 1) and Tom Durant-Pritchard (guest season 2)