-- 101 102 104 105 109 -->\n* [[Kate Phillips]] as Venetia Scott <!-- 101 102 104 -->\n* [[Ronald Pickup]] as the [[Geoffrey Fisher|Archbishop of Canterbury]] <!-- 101 103 105 110 -->\n* Nigel Cooke as [[Harry Crookshank]] <!-- 101 102 104 109 -->\n* [[Patrick Drury]] as the [[Roger Lumley, 11th Earl of Scarbrough|Lord Chamberlain]] <!-- 101 102 103 105 106 -->\n* [[John Woodvine]] as the [[Cyril Garbett|Archbishop of York]] <!-- 101 103 105 110 -->\n* [[Jo Stone-Fewings]] as Collins <!-- 104 109 -->\n* [[Tony Guilfoyle]] as the [[Michael Ramsey|Bishop of Durham]] <!-- 105 110 -->\n* Paul Thornley as Bill Mattheson <!-- 106 110 -->\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Season 2====<!-- List of NAMED characters recurring in season 2. -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Chloe Pirrie]] as Eileen Parker <!-- 201 202 203 -->\n* [[Nicholas Burns (actor)|Nicholas Burns]] as [[Anthony Nutting]] <!-- 201 203 -->\n* [[Lucy Russell (actress)|Lucy Russell]] as [[Edwina Mountbatten, Countess Mountbatten of Burma|Lady Mountbatten]] <!-- 201 202 204 -->\n* Richard Elfyn as [[Selwyn Lloyd]] <!-- 201 203 206 207 -->\n* [[Adrian Lukis]] as Vice-Admiral Sir [[Conolly Abel Smith]] <!-- 202 203 -->\n* Guy Williams as [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]] <!-- 202 209 -->\n* [[Simon Paisley Day]] as Meryn Lewis <!-- 202 203 -->\n* [[Sylvestra Le Touzel]] as [[Lady Dorothy Macmillan|Dorothy Macmillan]] <!-- 204 205 208 210 -->\n* Catherine Bailey as [[Lady Elizabeth Cavendish|Elizabeth Cavendish]] <!-- 204 207 -->\n* [[Paul Clayton (actor)|Paul Clayton]] as [[Robert Boothby, Baron Boothby|Bob Boothby]] <!-- 204 210 -->\n* Yolanda Kettle as Camilla Fry <!-- 204 207 -->\n* [[Ed Cooper Clarke]] as [[Jeremy Fry]] <!-- 204 207 -->\n* [[Ryan Sampson]] as [[Dudley Moore]] <!-- 204 210 -->\n* Tim Steed as [[John Profumo]] <!-- 204 210 -->\n* Lyla Barrett-Rye as school-aged Princess Anne <!-- 205 207 209 210 -->\n* Robert Irons as Freddie Bishop <!-- 206 208 -->\n* Patrick Warner as [[Peter Cook]] <!-- 207 210 -->\n* [[Oliver Maltman]] as [[James Orr (courtier)|Jim Orr]] <!-- 207 210 -->\n* David Annen as [[Alec Douglas-Home]] <!-- 208 210 -->\n* [[Richard Lintern]] as [[Stephen Ward]] <!-- 209 210 -->\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Season 3====<!-- List of NAMED characters recurring in season 3. -->\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Penny Downie]] as [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester|Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]]<!-- 301, 302, 304, 307, 310 -->\n* [[Mark Dexter]] as [[Tony Benn]], Labour politician<ref name=\"RadioTimesCastPage2\"/><!-- 301, 303, 304, 305, 306 -->\n* [[Lorraine Ashbourne]] as [[Barbara Castle]], Labour politician<ref name=\"RadioTimesCastPage2\" /><!-- 301, 303, 304, 305, 306 -->\n* [[Aden Gillett]] as [[Richard Crossman]]<!-- 301, 303, 304 -->\n* [[Sinead Matthews|Sin\u00e9ad Matthews]] as [[Marcia Falkender, Baroness Falkender|Marcia Williams]], Labour politician who served as Harold Wilson's private secretary<ref name=\"RadioTimesCastPage2\" /><!-- 303, 305, 306 -->\n* David Charles as [[George Thomas, 1st Viscount Tonypandy|George Thomas]]<!-- 303, 306 -->\n* [[Stuart McQuarrie]] as [[George Thomson, Baron Thomson of Monifieth]]<!-- 305, 306 -->\n* [[Connie M'Gadzah]] as Sydney Johnson<!-- 308, 309 -->\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Series overview\n| released    = y\n| allreleased = y\n\n| color1      = #190406\n| link1       = #Season 1 (2016)\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2016|11|4}}\n\n| color2      = #2F4F4F\n| link2       = #Season 2 (2017)\n| episodes2   = 10\n| start2      = {{Start date|2017|12|8}}\n\n| color3      = #12573B\n| link3       = #Season 3 (2019)\n| episodes3   = 10\n| start3      = {{Start date|2019|11|17}}\n}}\n\n===Season 1 (2016)===\n{{main|The Crown (season 1)}}\n{{:The Crown (season 1)}}\n\n===Season 2 (2017)===\n{{main|The Crown (season 2)}}\n{{:The Crown (season 2)}}\n\n===Season 3 (2019)===\n{{main|The Crown (season 3)}}\n{{:The Crown (season 3)}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn November 2014, it was announced that Netflix was to adapt the 2013 stage play  ''[[The Audience (2013 play)|The Audience]]'' into a television series.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30034850|publisher=BBC|website=www.bbc.co.uk|date=13 November 2014|title=Netflix to adapt Queen Elizabeth II play The Audience}}</ref> [[Peter Morgan]], who wrote the 2006 film ''[[The Queen (2006 film)|The Queen]]'' and the play, is the main scriptwriter for ''The Crown''.<ref name=\"PeterMorgan\">{{Cite news|title=Netflix plans original UK drama about the Queen |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27539739 |work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016 |date=May 23, 2014}}</ref> The directors of the television series who were also involved in the stage production are [[Stephen Daldry]], [[Philip Martin (director)|Philip Martin]], [[Julian Jarrold]], and [[Benjamin Caron]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The Crown is a 'game changer for British drama' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/netflix/the-crown-game-changer-for-british-drama/ |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |date=October 17, 2016}}</ref> The first 10-part season was the most expensive drama produced by Netflix and [[Left Bank Pictures]] to date, costing at least \u00a3100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Made in the UK:The Crown |url=http://www.britishfilmcommission.org.uk/made-in-the-uk-the-crown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120010308/http://www.britishfilmcommission.org.uk/made-in-the-uk-the-crown/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 20, 2016 |website=British Film Commission |accessdate=November 19, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2016/07/12/the-crown-everything-you-need-to-know-about-netflixs-100-million/ |title=The Crown: the Royal family are 'nervous' about Netflix's new \u00a3100 million series |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=August 2, 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/06/19/matt-smith-starring-in-netflix-series-the-crown |title=Matt Smith starring in Netflix series, The Crown |website=IGN |date=June 19, 2015 |accessdate=June 22, 2015 |first=Anthony |last=Couto}}</ref> A second season was commissioned,<ref>{{cite news |title=Netflix's glittering Crown could leave BBC looking a little dull |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/oct/31/netflix-glittering-crown-bbc-dull-launch-tv |work=[[The Guardian]] |author= Martinson, Jane|accessdate=October 31, 2016 |date=November 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TelegraphOct2016\">{{cite news |title=The Crown is a 'game changer for British drama' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/netflix/the-crown-game-changer-for-british-drama/ |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |date=November 4, 2016}}</ref> with the series intended to span 60 episodes over six seasons.<ref name=\"telegraph\" /> By October 2017, \"early production\" had begun on an anticipated third and fourth season,<ref name=\"ColmanCast\" /> and by the following January, Netflix confirmed the series had been renewed for a third and fourth season.<ref name=\"THRSeason3&4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/crown-season-3-all-details-far-1077716|title='The Crown' Season 3: All the Details (So Far)|last=Bentley|first=Jean|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 24, 2018|accessdate=January 24, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6wj076dsM?url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/crown-season-3-all-details-far-1077716|archivedate=January 25, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In January 2020, it was announced that the series had been renewed for a fifth and final season. Speaking to ending the series with five seasons, after it had been intended to last six, Morgan said while crafting the stories for season five, \"it has become clear to me that this is the perfect time and place to stop\"; Netflix and Sony supported Morgan's decision.<ref name=\"FinalSeasonAnnounce\" />\n\n===Casting===\nBy November 2014, [[Claire Foy]] had entered negotiations to portray Queen Elizabeth II in the series.<ref name=\"FoyCast\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/netflix-finds-its-queen-in-claire-foy-1201281387/|title=Netflix's 'The Crown' Finds Its Queen In Claire Foy|last=Jaafar|first=Ali|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> By May 2015, [[Vanessa Kirby]] was in negotiations to portray Princess Margaret.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/vanessa-kirby-princess-margaret-the-crown-1201427873/|title=Vanessa Kirby To Play Princess Margaret In Netflix's 'The Crown'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> In June 2015, [[John Lithgow]] was cast as Winston Churchill, and [[Matt Smith (actor)|Matt Smith]] was cast as Prince Philip; Foy was confirmed as Queen Elizabeth II.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/netflix-the-crown-cast-matt-smith-claire-foy-john-lithgow-1201523102/|title='Doctor Who' Alum Matt Smith Cast in Netflix's 'The Crown' with John Lithgow, Claire Foy|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref> Also starring in the first season were [[Victoria Hamilton]], [[Jared Harris]], and [[Eileen Atkins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/09/the-crown-netflix-series-1201827104/|title='The Crown' Trailer: First Look At Netflix's Queen Elizabeth Drama Series|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=27 September 2016|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Left Bank producers noted that Smith was paid more than Foy in the first two seasons, partially because of his ''[[Doctor Who]]'' fame.<ref name=\"FoySmithPay\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-crown-season-3-donald-trump-megan-markle-1202725163/|title=Claire Foy Was Paid Less Than Matt Smith on 'The Crown'|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> This information brought up discussion on the [[gender pay gap]], including the creation of a petition asking Smith to donate the difference between his and Foy's salary to the [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] Legal Defense Fund.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/petition-matt-smith-the-crown-salary-times-up-1202729883/|title=Petition Calls on Matt Smith to Donate Part of His Salary From 'The Crown' to Time's Up|last=Clarke|first=Stewart|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> Left Bank later issued an apology to Foy and Smith for putting them \"at the center of a media storm... through no fault of their own.\" Left Bank also clarified that they \"are responsible for budgets and salaries; the actors are not aware of who gets what, and cannot be held personally responsible for the pay of their colleagues.\" They added that they support \"the drive for gender equality in film and TV and [were] eager to talk to the British Time\u2019s Up campaign and [were] already speaking to Era 50:50, a group campaigning for gender equality on screen and stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-crown-producers-apologize-to-claire-foy-matt-smith-1202731165/|title='The Crown' Producers Apologize to Claire Foy, Matt Smith Over Gender Pay Scandal|last=Clarke|first=Stewart|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=20 March 2018|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref> Suzanne Mackie, Left Bank's creative director, did note that moving forward, no other actor would be paid more than the actress portraying the Queen.<ref name=\"FoySmithPay\" /> Regarding the controversy, Foy was \"not [surprised about the interest in the story] in the sense that it was a female-led drama. I'm not surprised that people saw [the story] and went, 'Oh, that's a bit odd.' But I know that Matt feels the same that I do, that it's odd to find yourself at the center [of a story] that you didn't particularly ask for.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/03/24/claire-foy-the-crown-pay-controversy/|title=Claire Foy talks The Crown pay controversy: 'I'm not surprised people went, \"That's a bit odd\"'|last=Collis|first=Clark|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=March 24, 2018|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Smith noted that he supported Foy and was \"pleased that it was resolved and [the producers] made amends for it because that's what needed to happen.\" ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' noted it was unclear what Smith was referring to as resolved, since Netflix and Left Bank had not commented on the matter further.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/matt-smith-crown-claire-foy-pay-disparity-tribeca-film-festival-2018-1104842|title='The Crown' Star Matt Smith Breaks Silence on Claire Foy Pay-Disparity Controversy| last=Lewis| first=Hilary|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=22 April 2018|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> Foy later described reports that she had received backpay to bring her salary up to parity as \"not quite correct\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/culture/culture-news/a22582948/claire-foy-gender-pay-gap-back-pay-the-crown/|title=Claire Foy won't receive back pay for her role in 'The Crown' after gender pay gap dispute|last=Fowler|first=Danielle|date=29 July 2018|website=Harper's BAZAAR|language=en-GB|access-date=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe producers recast the continuing roles with older actors every two seasons, as the timeline moves forward and the characters age.<ref name=\"RecastActors\" /> In October 2017, [[Olivia Colman]] was cast as Queen Elizabeth II for the third and fourth seasons.<ref name=\"ColmanCast\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/olivia-colman-the-crown-queen-elizabeth-season-3-1202600405/|title=Olivia Colman Joins 'The Crown' as Queen Elizabeth for Seasons 3 and 4|last=Birnbaum|first=Olivia|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=26 October 2017|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> By January 2018, [[Helena Bonham Carter]] and [[Paul Bettany]] were in negotiations to portray Princess Margaret and Prince Philip, respectively, for these seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/the-crown-helena-bonham-carter-talks-princess-margaret-1202236329/|title='The Crown': Helena Bonham Carter Poised To Play Princess Margaret|last=Petski|first=Denise|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=5 January 2018|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"BettanyTalks\">{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/01/20/the-crown-paul-bettany-negotiations-prince-philip/|title=The Crown: Paul Bettany in talks to play Prince Philip|last=Maslow|first=Nick|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=20 January 2018|accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> However, by the end of the month Bettany was forced to drop out due to the time commitment required.<ref name=\"BettanyOut\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/01/the-crown-prince-philip-season-3|title=The Crown's Third Season Is Minus a Prince Philip as Paul Bettany Bows Out|last=Miller|first=Julie|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=25 January 2018|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> By the end of March 2018, [[Tobias Menzies]] was cast as Prince Philip for the third and fourth seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/the-crown-tobias-menzies-prince-philip-matt-smith-netflix-1202354968/|title='The Crown' Sets 'Outlander's Tobias Menzies As New Prince Philip|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=28 March 2018|date=28 March 2018}}</ref> In early May 2018, Bonham Carter was confirmed to have been cast, alongside [[Jason Watkins (actor)|Jason Watkins]] as Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]].<ref name=\"CarterConfirm\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-crown-season-3-helena-bonham-carter-jason-watkins-1202796598/|title='The Crown' Officially Casts Helena Bonham Carter, Adds Jason Watkins for Season 3|last=Otterson|first=Joe|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=3 May 2018|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref> The next month, [[Ben Daniels]] was cast as Antony Armstrong-Jones for the third season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/the-exorcist-star-ben-daniels-to-play-antony-armstrong-jones-in-season-three-of-the-crown-1202414111/|title='The Crown': 'The Exorcist' Star Ben Daniels To Play Antony Armstrong-Jones In Season 3 Of Netflix's Royal Drama|last=White|first=Peter|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=20 June 2018|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref> along with [[Erin Doherty]] joining the series as [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/crowns-princess-anne-be-played-by-erin-doherty-1122586|title='The Crown' Casts Its Princess Anne (Exclusive)|last=Sandberg|first=Bryn Elise|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref> A month later, [[Josh O'Connor]] and [[Marion Bailey]] were cast as Prince Charles and the Queen Mother, respectively, for the third and fourth seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/the-crown-josh-oconnor-prince-charles-marion-bailey-queen-mother-1202886865/|title='The Crown': Josh O'Connor to Play Prince Charles, Marion Bailey the Queen Mother|last=Clarke|first=Stewart|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=26 July 2018 |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, [[Emerald Fennell]] was cast as [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Camilla Shand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/10/23/the-crown-casts-call-the-midwife-actress-emerald-fennell-as-camilla-parker-bowles/|title=The Crown casts Call the Midwife actress Emerald Fennell as Camilla Parker Bowles|last=Kinane|first=Ruth|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=23 October 2018|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, [[Charles Dance]] was cast as Louis Mountbatten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a25605617/the-crown-season-3-charles-dance/ |title=The Crown season 3 adds Charles Dance to cast \u2013 and here's who he's playing |last=Edwards|first=Chris|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=17 December 2018|accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Emma Corrin was cast as [[Diana, Princess of Wales|Lady Diana Spencer]] for the fourth season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ellievhall/the-crown-casts-princess-diana-season-4|title=\"The Crown\" Just Cast Its Princess Diana|last=Hall|first=Ellie|work=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref> [[Gillian Anderson]], who had been rumoured since January 2019 to be in talks to portray [[Margaret Thatcher]] in the fourth season, was officially confirmed for the role in September 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/gillian-anderson-the-crown-margaret-thatcher-netflix-1203327451/ |title=Gillian Anderson Joins \u2018The Crown\u2019 as Margaret Thatcher |last=Nickolai |first=Nate |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=7 September 2019 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/ikrd/gillian-anderson-the-crown-netflix-margaret-thatcher |title=Gillian Anderson Will Be Playing Margaret Thatcher In \"The Crown\" |last=Dahir |first=Ikran |work=[[BuzzFeed News]]|date=7 September 2019 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/the-crown-officially-confirms-gillian-anderson-as-margaret-thatcher-for-season-four-1202728647/ |title=\u2018The Crown\u2019 Officially Confirms Gillian Anderson As Margaret Thatcher For Season Four |last=Dahir |first=Ikran |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=7 September 2019 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Imelda Staunton]] was announced as succeeding Colman as the Queen for the fifth and final season.<ref name=\"FinalSeasonAnnounce\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/global/the-crown-will-end-after-season-five-with-imelda-staunton-as-queen-elizabeth-1203488171/|title=\u2018The Crown\u2019 Will End After Season 5 With Imelda Staunton as Queen Elizabeth|last=Ravindran|first=Manori|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nAn estimated 25% of the first season was filmed at [[Elstree Studios (Shenley Road)|Elstree Studios]] in [[Borehamwood]], Hertfordshire, with the remainder filmed on location, altogether taking 152 days. Sets for private quarters, the interior of a private jet, the cabinet room, and the exterior of [[10 Downing Street]], were built at Elstree Studios,<ref name=\"TelegraphOct2016\" /><ref name=\"LocationGuide\" /> while [[Lancaster House]], [[Wrotham Park]] and [[Wilton House]] were used to double as [[Buckingham Palace]]. [[Ely Cathedral]] and Winchester Cathedral stood in for [[Westminster Abbey]], while locations in South Africa doubled as Kenya.<ref name=\"TelegraphOct2016\" /> Additional locations in the UK included [[Waddesdon Manor]], [[Eltham Palace]], the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich|Royal Naval College]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-09/the-crown-where-was-it-filmed |title=The Crown: Where was it filmed? |website=[[Radio Times]] |date=January 9, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> [[Goldsmiths' Hall]], [[Brighton City Airport|Shoreham Airport]], [[New Slains Castle]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-01-09/the-crown-where-was-it-filmed-2 |title=The Crown: Where was it filmed? Page 2 |website=Radio Times |date=January 9, 2017 |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> [[Balmoral Castle]], [[Cruden Bay]], [[Lyceum Theatre, London|Lyceum Theatre]], [[Loseley Park]], [[Hatfield House]],<ref name=\"LocationGuide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelocationguide.com/2016/11/netflix-period-drama-the-crown-filmed-on-location-throughout-the-uk-and-south-africa/ |title=Netflix period drama The Crown filmed on location throughout the UK and South Africa |last=Deehan |first=Tom |website=The Location Guide |date=November 4, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> [[Chatham Dockyard|The Historic Dockyard Chatham]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/2016/10/the-crown-2016/ |title=The Crown (2016) |website=Kent Film Office |date=October 31, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> [[Southwark Cathedral]], [[Ardverikie House]], [[Englefield House]],  [[Wellington College, Berkshire|Wellington College]], the [[Great Central Railway (heritage railway)]] and the [[Glenfeshie Estate]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://moviepilot.com/p/netflix-the-crown-drama-filming-locations/4138042 |title='The Crown': Where Was The Expensive New Drama Filmed? |last=Fedko-Blake |first=Vaira |website=Movie Pilot |date=November 7, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211075123/https://moviepilot.com/p/netflix-the-crown-drama-filming-locations/4138042 |archivedate=February 11, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Filming on the second season began in early October 2016.<ref name=\"RecastActors\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a812828/the-crown-will-replace-matt-smith-claire-foy-and-its-entire-cast-after-two-seasons/ |title=The Crown will replace Matt Smith, Claire Foy and its ENTIRE CAST after two seasons |last=Jeffrey |first=Morgan |website=Digital Spy |date=November 1, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> Each episode of the first two seasons would shoot for about 22 days, with each costing about {{GBP|5 million}} ({{US$|7 million}}) to produce.<ref name=\"FoySmithPay\" /> The third season began filming in July 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/958541-new-the-crown-season-3-photos-featuring-helena-bonham-carter|title=New The Crown Season 3 Photos Featuring Helena Bonham Carter|last=Frederick|first=Clint|website=[[ComingSoon.net]]|date=July 18, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> and concluded in February 2019. The fourth season began filming in August 2019 and wrapped in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-03-19/the-crown-season-3-netflix-release-date-cast-characters-plot-news-trailer-olivia-colman/|title=When is The Crown season 3 on Netflix? Who is in the cast, and what is going to happen?|last=Gill|first=James|website=[[RadioTimes]]|accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/the-crown-season-4-coronavirus/|title='The Crown' season 4 completes filming early during coronavirus pandemic|website=EW.com|language=EN|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nThe re-enactment of the removal of the King's cancerous lung, originally performed by [[Clement Price Thomas|Sir Clement Price Thomas]], was researched and planned by [[Pankaj Chandak]], specialist in transplant surgery at Guy's Hospital, London. Chandak and his surgical team then became part of the actual scene filmed for the show.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.aol.co.uk/entertainment/2016/11/05/surgeons-replace-actors-in-the-crowns-king-george-vi-operation/ |title=Surgeons replace actors in The Crown's King George VI operation scene |date=November 5, 2016 |website=AOL UK |access-date=April 11, 2017}}</ref> The surgical model of King George VI was donated to the [[Gordon Museum of Pathology]] for use as a teaching aid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alumni.kcl.ac.uk/news-features/the-gordon-museum|title=Inside the Gordon Museum \u2013 King's Alumni Community|website=alumni.kcl.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\nThe show has been commended for its depiction of events, although it has occasionally faced criticism for excessive dramatisation and for some events that bear no relation to the historical evidence.<ref name=\u201ca29873503\u201d>{{Cite news|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/arts-and-culture/a29873503/the-crown-netflix-tv-show-accuracy/|title=Is\u00a0The Crown\u00a0Accurate? The Answer Is Complicated|last=HALLEMANN|first=CAROLINE|date=2019-11-23|work=Town and Country|access-date=2019-11-26|language=en-UK}}</ref> [[Peggy Noonan]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' commented on the historical inaccuracy of the series, and argued for \"more truth in art and entertainment\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lies-of-the-crown-and-the-post-1514505833|title=The Lies of \u2018The Crown\u2019 and \u2018The Post\u2019|last=Noonan|first=Peggy|date=2017-12-29|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-06-19|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> \n\nThe series has portrayed characters who had died prior to the events depicted, notably [[Baron (photographer)|Baron Nahum]] who continued to be featured in the second season, but in reality had died by then. [[Prince William of Gloucester]] is logically present in the first season, but by the third season's depiction of the [[Silver Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Silver Jubilee]] he had died five years earlier.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-accurate-is-the-crown-we-sort-fact-from-fiction-in-the-royal-drama-8g708rz2c|title=How accurate is The Crown? We sort fact from fiction in the royal drama|date=17 November 2019|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=5 December 2019|language=en-UK}}</ref> \n\n====Season 1====\n\nIn reality there was no dispute over [[Michael Adeane, Baron Adeane|Michael Adeane]] being the natural successor to [[Alan Lascelles|Tommy Lascelles]] as Private Secretary. [[Martin Charteris, Baron Charteris of Amisfield|Martin Charteris]] accordingly took the role in 1972.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-12-16/the-crown-who-was-the-real-martin-charteris/|title=The Crown: Who was the real Martin Charteris?|date=12 December 2016|work=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=12 December 2016|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nChurchill's wife Clementine is depicted overseeing the burning of his portrait by Graham Sutherland shortly after his retirement. In reality it was destroyed by their private secretary Grace Hamblin's brother without her involvement.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2019-03-26/the-crown-what-really-happened-to-graham-sutherlands-controversial-portrait-of-winston-churchill/|title=The Crown: What really happened to Graham Sutherland\u2019s controversial portrait of Winston Churchill?|date=12 December 2016|work=RadioTimes|access-date=12 December 2016|language=en-UK}}</ref> \n\nRoyal historian Hugo Vickers denied that Princess Margaret had acted as monarch whilst Queen Elizabeth was away on tour, and claimed that her speech at the ambassador's reception never happened. Martin Charteris was on tour with Queen Elizabeth and not in London during  these events. The Queen Mother bought the [[Castle of Mey]] a year earlier than shown and often looked after Charles and Anne whilst Queen Elizabeth was away.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/royal/742554/the-crown-netflix-queen-elizabeth-mother-castle-buy-scotland-mey|title=The Crown: What castle did the Queen Mother buy in Scotland when she was in mourning?|author= Smith, Reiss|date=12 December 2016|work=[[Daily Express]]|access-date=12 December 2016|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nThe show has been interpreted as perpetuating the idea that the Queen and Churchill forced Princess Margaret to give up her plan to marry Group Captain Peter Townsend. In the series, the Queen tells her sister that, if she marries Townsend, she would no longer be a member of the family because of the [[Royal Marriages Act 1772]]. However, there is clear evidence that, in reality, efforts had been made to prevent any further delay of the marriage, which would have allowed Princess Margaret to keep her royal title and her civil list allowance, stay in the country, and continue with her public duties.<ref name=BBCMag38032464>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Reynolds |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-38032464 |title=Did the Queen stop Princess Margaret marrying Peter Townsend? |work=[[BBC News]] |date=November 19, 2016 |accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Season 2====\n\nThere is no evidence to suggest that Queen Elizabeth gave a speech at the [[Jaguar Cars]] factory, nor would she have met Lord Altrincham to discuss his article.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-03-26/the-crown-season-2-netflix-lord-altrincham/|title=The Crown: Who was the real Lord Altrincham?|work=RadioTimes|access-date=2019-12-06|language=en-UK}}</ref> \n\nVickers wrote that Queen Elizabeth did condemn the Duke of Windsor after she read the [[Marburg Files]], but claimed that the series gave a false implication that the Duke was banished from the royal family upon publication. He remained in contact with his family, and his public appearances continued.<ref>{{cite news| title= How accurate is The Crown? We sort fact from fiction in the royal drama |url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-accurate-is-the-crown-we-sort-fact-from-fiction-in-the-royal-drama-8g708rz2c | date = December 19, 2017| accessdate = August 14, 2018| work = [[The Times]]}}</ref> \n\nThe depiction of the relationship with Jackie Kennedy has drawn criticism. Reports indicate that she had described Prince Philip as \"nice but nervous\" and overall there was no bond between them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/12/queen-elizabeth-jackie-kennedy-the-crown-netflix|title=The Crown: What Really Happened When Queen Elizabeth Met John and Jackie Kennedy|last=Miller|first=Julie|date=2017-12-08|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=2019-01-11|language=en-US}}</ref> The implication that Queen Elizabeth visited Ghana to compete with Jackie Kennedy's popularity was ridiculed by critics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/899648/The-Crown-season-2-Netflix-Queen-Jackie-Kennedy-Jodi-Balfour|title=The Crown season 2: What happened between the Queen and Jackie Kennedy? Were they friends?|last=DEBNATH|first=Neela|date=2018-01-04|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> Reviews of the episode noted that it ignored more significant events of the visit, such as Kennedy's sister [[Lee Radziwill|Lee]] and her husband [[Stanis\u0142aw Albrecht Radziwi\u0142\u0142|Prince Stanis\u0142aw Albrecht Radziwi\u0142\u0142's]] initial exclusion from the banquet invitation list given both were divorcees. Both were eventually invited,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/royalty/2017120844640/look-back-queen-meeting-kennedys/|title=A look back at the Queen meeting the Kennedys ahead of season two of The Crown|last=Shahid|first=Sharnaz|date=2018-12-08|work=Hello|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> though Princess Margaret and [[Princess Marina of Greece and Denmark|Princess Marina]] did not attend, despite the Kennedys apparently wanting to meet them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a13128840/john-kennedy-jackie-kennedy-queen-elizabeth-meeting-buckingham-palace/|title=The True Story of How the Kennedys Met the Queen|last=Hallemann|first=Caroline|date=2018-12-19|work=Town and Country|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Gordonstoun]] School responded to its negative portrayal, claiming that Prince Charles's personal feedback to the school had been overwhelmingly positive.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=Colditz in kilts? Charles loved it, says old school as Gordonstoun hits back at The Crown|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/12/10/prince-charles-school-hits-back-crown-colditz-kilts-portrayal/|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author= Rudgard, Olivia |accessdate=April 28, 2018|date=December 10, 2017}}</ref> Royal historian Hugo Vickers said that the same episode inaccurately depicted Philip's sister's death in a plane crash as having arisen from his own misbehaviour at Gordonstoun: \"It is beyond me how serious film-makers would wish to turn such a dreadful tragedy into a series of invented scenes bearing no relation to the truth.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nPhil Owen of ''The Wrap'' saw dry comedy in Northam's portrayal of Prime Minister Anthony Eden, stating: \"I'm assuming that creator Peter Morgan meant for it to be comedy. There's really no other explanation for why Jeremy Northam played Prime Minister Anthony Eden like he's having a nervous breakdown in every scene.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= 'The Crown' Season 2 Review: Just Trashy Enough to Work|url=https://www.thewrap.com/crown-season-2-review-just-trashy-enough-work/|website=TheWrap| accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Season 3====\n\nQueen Elizabeth did not visit Winston Churchill following his final stroke. Vickers claims that by then Churchill was senile and incapable of holding a conversation.<ref name=\u201c1207400\u201d>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1207400/The-Crown-season-3-fact-checked-errors-historical-inaccuracies-Princess-Alice|title=The Crown season 3 fact-checked: What are the biggest errors and historical inaccuracies? |last=Debnath|first=Neela|date=21 November 2019|work=[[Daily Express]]|access-date=26 November 2019|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nSir [[Anthony Blunt]]'s exposure as a Soviet spy has drawn criticism. Vickers noted that the episode did not mention that he was publicly exposed in 1979 and stripped of his knighthood, whilst also noting that he never resided at Buckingham Palace and ridiculing a scene in which he discusses his exposure with Prince Philip in an attempt to blackmail the royal family.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Eleanor Bley| last= Griffiths |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-11-17/the-crown-anthony-blunt-season-three/|title=Was the Queen\u2019s art adviser Anthony Blunt really a Soviet spy? Truth behind The Crown|date=17 November 2019|work=[[Radio Times]]|access-date=6 December 2019|language=en-UK}}</ref> \n\nThe depiction of the relationship with President Johnson has been criticised. It has been suggested that he did not refuse to attend Churchill's funeral, in response to Harold Wilson's refusal to support the [[Vietnam War]], and that the president was genuinely unable to attend due to poor health.  His disappointment with Wilson's views on Vietnam had developed much later.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Ciara |last=Nugent|url=https://time.com/5333083/queen-elizabeth-trump-visit-presidents/|title=Here's How Every Meeting Between the Queen and a U.S. President Went|access-date=10 December 2019|work=[[Time (magazine)| Time]]|date=3 June 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> Historians also denied the episode's implication that no US President had ever been to Balmoral. [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] had visited Balmoral whilst president in 1959.<ref>{{Cite magazine|first=Chloe |last=Foussaines|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a29311370/duke-of-windsor-death-true-story/|title=Here's How Every Meeting Between the Queen and a U.S. President Went|date=12 July 2018|work=[[Time (magazine)| Time]]|access-date=6 December 2019|language=en-UK}}</ref> Critics noted that the episode did not mention that Johnson is the only president since [[Harry S. Truman]] never to have met the monarch.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|first=Marie |last=Claire|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/a29776788/lyndon-b-johnson-the-queen-reject-balmoral-the-crown/|title=Did LBJ Reject The Queen's Invitation to Visit the U.K.?|date=17 November 2019|work=[[Marie Claire]]|access-date=6 December 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> The implication that Johnson did not know who Princess Margaret was before her November 1965 visit to America was criticised by critics.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /> Princess Margaret was at a White House dinner during that visit, but the details are mostly fictional (such as her carousing with President Johnson and kissing him, dirty limericks, and helping secure a US bailout, which was in fact negotiated earlier, in September 1965).<ref>{{Cite news|first=Madison|last=Feller|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a29775483/the-crown-princess-margaret-america-white-house-lyndon-johnson/|title=The Crown: The True Story Of Princess Margaret\u2019s 1965 Trip To America| date= 16 November 2019 |work=Elle|access-date=21 December 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Suyin|last=Haynes|url=https://time.com/5722112/the-crown-princess-margaret/|title=The True Story Behind Princess Margaret's Storyline on The Crown Season 3|date=2019-11-15|work=Time|access-date=2019-12-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe relationship with Princess Alice has also drawn criticism for Philip's depiction as being estranged from his mother and objecting to her visiting London. In fact he visited her regularly and often transported her by plane, and her depicted interview with a journalist from ''[[The Guardian]]'' never happened. Vickers also stated that the same episode ignored that Philip encouraged her to move to London permanently.<ref name=\u201c1207400\u201d/>\n\nPrince Charles did visit the Duke of Windsor in Paris in 1972,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a29322538/prince-charles-duke-of-windsor-edward-viii-relationship-the-crown-true-story/|title=Inside Prince Charles's Relationship with the Duke of Windsor|last=FOUSSIANES|first=CHLOE|date=2019-11-23|work=Town and Country|access-date=2019-11-26|language=en-UK}}</ref> however the depiction of letters concerning his affections for Camilla Shand was criticised; Charles and Camilla had met but were not intimately close during the Duke's lifetime.<ref name=\u201ca29873503\u201d /><ref name=\u201c1207400\u201d /> Queen Elizabeth did visit the Duke ten days before his death, but this had been long-planned and not requested at short notice.<ref name=\u201c1207400\u201d /> Wallis Simpson was not by the Duke's side at the time of his death.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|first=Chloe |last=Foussaines|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a29311370/duke-of-windsor-death-true-story/|title=The Duke of Windsor Did Die in Exile\u2014Not Unlike\u00a0The Crown's Version of Events|date=2019-11-29|work=Town and Country|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nThe timeframe of Robin Woods's posting as Dean of Windsor around the time of the [[Apollo 11|Apollo 11 spaceflight and lunar landing]] in July 1969 is inaccurate. He took the role in 1962.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/society/tradition/a29642775/robin-woods-dean-of-windsor-the-crown/|title=Who Was Prince Philip's Friend Robin Woods, the Dean of Windsor?|last=HUBBARD|first=LAUREN|date=2019-11-30|work=Town and Country|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-accurate-is-the-crown-we-sort-fact-from-fiction-in-the-royal-drama-8g708rz2c|title=How accurate is The Crown? We sort fact from fiction in the royal drama|date=2019-11-17|work=The Times|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n\nIt has been suggested that there wasn't any plot by the palace to prevent Charles and Camilla's marriage, with Camilla's love for Andrew Parker Bowles being genuine and Charles unable to decide.<ref name=\u201cfact-from-fiction\u201d /><ref>{{Cite news|first=Julie |last=Miller|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/prince-charles-camilla-parker-bowles-anne-andrew-the-crown|title=The Crown:\u00a0The Truth About the Romances of Charles, Camilla, Anne, and Andrew|date=2019-11-18|work=Vanity Fair|access-date=2019-12-06|language=en-US}}</ref> It has also been suggested that Princess Anne's relations with Andrew Parker Bowles did not overlap with Charles and Camilla's introduction. Reviews of the episode noted that it ignored more significant events, citing Anne's 1973 wedding to [[Mark Phillips|Captain Mark Phillips]] and her attempted kidnapping in 1974.<ref name=\u201ca29873503\u201d />\n\n==Release==\nThe series's first two episodes were released theatrically in the United Kingdom on November 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/crown-film |title=''The Crown'' [Season 1, Episodes 1 & 2] (15) |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=October 25, 2016 |accessdate=October 26, 2016}}</ref> The first season was released worldwide in its entirety on November 4, 2016.<ref name=\"PremiereDate\">{{cite web |title=Matt Smith's Netflix drama The Crown gets premiere date |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/04/11/matt-smith-netflix-crown-premiere-date |website=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=April 12, 2016 |first=Dylan |last=Kickham |date=April 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Claire Foy and Matt Smith face the challenges of royal life in new extended trailer for Netflix drama The Crown |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-09-27/claire-foy-and-matt-smith-face-the-challenges-of-royal-life-in-new-extended-trailer-for-netflix-drama-the-crown |website=Radio Times |accessdate=September 27, 2016 |date=September 27, 2016}}</ref> The second season was released on December 8, 2017.<ref name=\"Season2Release\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/the-crown-season-2-premiere-date-first-trailer-1202522364/|title='The Crown' Season 2 Sets Premiere Date, Releases First Trailer|last=Otterson|first=Joe|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The third season was released on November 17, 2019.<ref name=\"on-demand\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2019-07-25/the-crown-season-3-netflix-release-date-cast-characters-plot-news-trailer-olivia-colman/|title=When is The Crown season 3 on Netflix? Who is in the cast, and what is going to happen?|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref><ref name=\"CarterConfirm\" /><ref name=\"SecondHalfof2019\">{{cite web|title=\u2018The Crown\u2019 Season 3 Set To Launch On Netflix In Second Half Of 2019; \u2018The Witcher\u2019 Set For Q4|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/the-crown-season-three-second-half-2019-1202597043/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Season3\">{{cite web|title=\u2018The Crown Season 3 (Finally!) Gets November Premiere Date at Netflix|url=https://tvline.com/2019/08/12/the-crown-season-3-premiere-date-netflix/|work=[[TVLine]]|date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeason 1 was released on DVD and Blu-ray in the United Kingdom on October 16, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Crown-Season-1-DVD/dp/B071Z24LPH |title=The Crown: Season 1 [DVD] [2017] |website=[[amazon.co.uk]] |date=October 16, 2017 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> and released worldwide on November 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8302/the-crown |title= The Crown (TV Series) |website=dvdsreleasedates.com |date=November 7, 2017 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Season 2 was released on DVD and Blu-ray in the United Kingdom on October 22, 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Crown-Season-2-DVD/dp/B07GJD714Y |title=The Crown \u2013 Season 2 [DVD] [2018] |website=[[amazon.co.uk]] |date=September 28, 2018 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> and was released worldwide on November 13, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8302/the-crown |title= The Crown (TV Series) |website=dvdsreleasedates.com |date=November 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n[[File:John Lithgow 8 by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|125px|right|[[John Lithgow]] won multiple awards for his performance as [[Winston Churchill]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#190406;\"|\n| 1\n| 89% (70 reviews)\n| 81 (29 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#2F4F4F;\"|\n| 2\n| 90% (82 reviews)\n| 87 (27 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#12573B;\"|\n| 3\n| 90% (98 reviews)\n| 84 (30 reviews)\n|}\n\nIn September 2019, ''The Guardian'' ranked the show 44th on its list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century, characterising it as \"filigree telly\", and calling \"every painstakingly staged scene a plush indulgence\" but having \"enough grit to make it more than just a luxury\".<ref name=Guardian_20190926>{{cite news |title= The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |work=The Guardian |date=16 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101054025/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |archivedate=1 November 2019| url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported 89% approval for the first season, based on 70 reviews with an average rating of 8.77/10. Its critical consensus reads, \"Powerful performances and lavish cinematography make ''The Crown'' a top-notch production worthy of its grand subject.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_crown/s01 |title=The Crown: Season 1 (2016) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the series holds a score of 81 out of 100, based on 29 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-crown |title=The Crown:Season 1 |website=Metacritic|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRotten Tomatoes reported a 90% approval rating for the second season based on 82 reviews, with an average rating of 8.35/10. The website's critical consensus reads \"''The Crown'' continues its reign with a self-assured sophomore season that indulges in high drama and sumptuous costumes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_crown/s02|title=The Crown:Season 2|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=November 5, 2019}}</ref> On Metacritic, the second season holds a score of 87 out of 100, based on 27 critics, retaining the first season's indication of \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |title= The Crown: Season 2|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-crown/season-2|website=metacritic|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 90% approval rating for the third season based on 98 reviews, with an average rating of 8.54/10. Its critical consensus reads: \"Olivia Colman shines, but as ''The Crown'' marches on in reliably luxurious fashion through time it finds space for the characters around her, providing ample opportunity for the appealing ensemble to gleam, too.\"<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_crown/s03|title=The Crown: Season 3|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105190952/https://rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_crown/s03|archive-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the season holds a score of 84 out of 100 based on 30 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-crown/season-3|title=The Crown \u2013 Season 3 reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=November 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108210235/https://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-crown/season-3|archive-date=November 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:98%\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3%;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:33%;\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:21%;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%;\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6%;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:1%;\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"5\" | 2016\n| [[American Film Institute Awards 2016|American Film Institute Awards]]\n| Top 10 TV Programs of the Year\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''The Crown''\n| {{won}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2016/12/afi-awards-tv-2016-game-of-thrones-this-is-us-stranger-things-1201867020/ |title=TV Honorees Heavy on Freshmen; 'This Is Us' Lone Network Show |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=December 8, 2016 |website=AFI Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[7th Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Television Awards]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Series|Best Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-awards |title=HBO leads television nominations for the 22nd Annual Critics' Choice awards with 22 nominations |website=Critics' Choice |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| [[John Lithgow]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Guest Performer in a Drama Series|Best Guest Performer in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Jared Harris]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Music in Media Awards]]\n| Best Main Title \u2013 TV Show/Digital Streaming Series\n| [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hmmawards.com/hmma-winners/ |title=HMMA Winners |website=Hollywood Music in Media Awards}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" ro