te web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/writers-guild-awards-2020-tv-nominations-1203426148/ |title=Writers Guild Unveils 2020 TV Award Nominees |first=Dave |last=McNary |date=December 5, 2019 |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama|Episodic Drama]]\n| Peter Morgan <small>(for \"Moondust\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| One-Hour Period or Fantasy Single-Camera Series\n| Martin Childs <small>(for \"Aberfan\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/awards/the-irishman-once-upon-a-time-the-mandalorian-art-directors-guild-nominations-1203429170/|title='The Irishman,' 'Once Upon a Time,' 'The Mandalorian' Among Art Directors Guild Nominations|last=Tangcay|first=Jazz|website=Variety|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[British royal family]]\n* [[The Crown]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title|80025678}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=4786824}}\n* {{Metacritic television|id=the-crown|title=The Crown}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes TV|the_crown|The Crown}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://guru.bafta.org/the-crown-masterclass |website=BAFTA Guru|title= The Crown: Masterclass|date= 28 February 2018}}\n\n{{The Crown (TV series)}}\n{{Elizabeth II|}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for ''The Crown''\n| list =\n{{GoldenGlobeTVDrama}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Drama Television Series}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n}}\n{{Peter Morgan}}\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crown, The}}\n[[Category:The Crown (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American political drama television series]]\n[[Category:Best Drama Series Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:British political drama television series]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Elizabeth II]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Winston Churchill]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George VI]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Gamal Abdel Nasser]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John F. Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John Profumo]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Louis Mountbatten, 1st Earl Mountbatten of Burma]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Left Bank Pictures]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Eric", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 3:cap>lc on non-titular use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Crown_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Kosmos 95", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Kosmos 95\n| mission_type          = [[Technology]]\n| operator              = \n| COSPAR_ID             = 1965-088A\n| SATCAT                = 01706\n| mission_duration      = 75 days\n\n| spacecraft_type       = DS-U2-V\n| manufacturer          = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n| launch_mass           = 325 kg <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n\n| launch_date           = 4 November 1965<br/>05:31:00 GMT <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Kosmos (rocket family)|Kosmos-2M]] 63S1M\n| launch_site           = [[Kapustin Yar]], [[Kapustin Yar|Site 86/1]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[Yuzhnoye Design Office|Yuzhnoye]]\n\n| decay_date            = 18 January 1966\n\n| orbit_epoch           = 4 November 1965\n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = 211 km \n| orbit_apoapsis        = 521 km\n| orbit_inclination     = 48.4\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = 91.7 minutes\n| apsis                 = gee\n}}\n'''Kosmos 95''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 95}} meaning ''Cosmos 95''), also known as '''DS-U2-V No.2''', was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[satellite]] of technology which was launched in 1965 as part of the [[Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik]] programme. It was a {{convert|325|kg}} spacecraft,<ref name=\"EA\"/> which was built by the [[Yuzhnoye Design Office]], and was used to conduct classified technology development experiments for the Soviet armed forces.<ref name=\"EA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsu2v.htm|title=DS-U2-V|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-12-06 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105020624/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsu2v.htm|archivedate=5 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kosmos (rocket family)|Kosmos-2M]] 63S1M<ref name=\"K2M\">{{cite web|url=http://www.friends-partners.org/partners/mwade/lvs/kos63s1m.htm|title=Kosmos 63S1M|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|date=2001-10-31|accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref> [[carrier rocket]] was used to launch Kosmos 95 into [[low Earth orbit]]. The launch took place from [[Kapustin Yar|Site 86/1]] at [[Kapustin Yar]].<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> The launch occurred at 05:31 GMT on 4 November 1965, and resulted in the successful insertion of the satellite into orbit.<ref name=\"EA-K2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|title=Kosmos 2|last=Wade |first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-12-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/690mZkz9v?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|archivedate=8 July 2012}}</ref> Upon reaching orbit, the satellite was assigned its [[Kosmos (satellite)|Kosmos]] designation, and received the [[International Designator]] 1965-088A. The [[North American Aerospace Defense Command |North American Air Defense Command]] assigned it the [[Satellite Catalog Number|catalogue number]] 01706.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1965-088A |title=Cosmos 95|publisher=US National Space Science Data Center|work=NSSDC Master Catalog|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref>\n\nKosmos 95 was the second of four [[DS-U2-V]] satellites to be launched.<ref name=\"EA\"/><ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/ds-u2-v.htm|title=DS-U2-V|first=Gunter|last=Krebs |publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> It was operated in an orbit with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|211|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|521|km}}, an [[inclination]] of 48.4\u00b0, and an [[orbital period]] of 91.7 minutes.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\"/> On 18 January 1966, it [[orbital decay|decayed]] from orbit and [[atmospheric re-entry|reentered]] the atmosphere.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\"WCS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacesecurity.org/files/WorldCivilSats2006.xls|title=World Civil Satellites 1957-2006|publisher=Space Security Index|accessdate=2009-12-06|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718022840/http://www.spacesecurity.org/files/WorldCivilSats2006.xls|archivedate=18 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n\n* [[1965 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1965}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0095}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1965]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites]]\n[[Category:Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik program]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Kosmos 95\n| mission_type          = [[Technology]]\n| operator              = \n| COSPAR_ID             = 1965-088A\n| SATCAT                = 01706\n| mission_duration      = 75 days\n\n| spacecraft_type       = [[DS-U2-V]]\n| manufacturer          = [[Yuzhnoye Design Bureau|Yuzhnoye]]\n| launch_mass           = 325 kg <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n\n| launch_date           = 4 November 1965<br/>05:31:00 GMT <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Kosmos (rocket family)|Kosmos-2M]] 63S1M\n| launch_site           = [[Kapustin Yar]], [[Kapustin Yar|Site 86/1]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[Yuzhnoye Design Bureau|Yuzhnoye]]\n\n| decay_date            = 18 January 1966\n\n| orbit_epoch           = 4 November 1965\n| orbit_reference       = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] <ref>https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/displayTrajectory.action?id=1965-088A - 27 February 2020</ref>\n| orbit_regime          = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis       = 211 km \n| orbit_apoapsis        = 521 km\n| orbit_inclination     = 48.4\u00b0\n| orbit_period          = 91.7 minutes\n| apsis                 = gee\n}}\n'''Kosmos 95''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441 95}} meaning ''Cosmos 95''), also known as '''DS-U2-V No.2''', was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[satellite]] of technology which was launched in 1965 as part of the [[Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik]] programme. It was a {{convert|325|kg}} spacecraft,<ref name=\"EA\"/> which was built by the [[Yuzhnoye Design Bureau]], and was used to conduct classified technology development experiments for the Soviet armed forces.<ref name=\"EA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsu2v.htm|title=DS-U2-V|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica |accessdate=2009-12-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105020624/http://www.astronautix.com/craft/dsu2v.htm|archivedate=5 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kosmos (rocket family)|Kosmos-2M]] 63S1M<ref name=\"K2M\">{{cite web|url=http://www.friends-partners.org/partners/mwade/lvs/kos63s1m.htm|title=Kosmos 63S1M|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|date=2001-10-31|accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref> [[carrier rocket]] was used to launch Kosmos 95 into [[low Earth orbit]]. The launch took place from [[Kapustin Yar|Site 86/1]] at [[Kapustin Yar]].<ref name=\"JSR-LL\">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> The launch occurred at 05:31 GMT on 4 November 1965, and resulted in the successful insertion of the satellite into orbit.<ref name=\"EA-K2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|title=Kosmos 2|last=Wade |first=Mark|publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica|accessdate=2009-12-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/690mZkz9v?url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/kosmos2.htm|archivedate=8 July 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Upon reaching orbit, the satellite was assigned its [[Kosmos (satellite)|Kosmos]] designation, and received the [[International Designator]] 1965-088A.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1965-088A|title=Cosmos 95|publisher=US National Space Science Data Center|work=NSSDC Master Catalog|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> The [[North American Aerospace Defense Command|North American Air Defense Command]] assigned it the [[Satellite Catalog Number|catalogue number]] 01706.\n\nKosmos 95 was the second of four [[DS-U2-V]] satellites to be launched.<ref name=\"EA\"/><ref name=\"GSP\">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/ds-u2-v.htm|title=DS-U2-V|first=Gunter|last=Krebs |publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> It was operated in an orbit with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|211|km}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|521|km}}, an 48.4\u00b0 of [[inclination]], and an [[orbital period]] of 91.7 minutes.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\"/> On 18 January 1966, it [[orbital decay|decayed]] from orbit and [[atmospheric re-entry|reentered]] the atmosphere.<ref name=\"JSR-SC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|last=McDowell|first=Jonathan|publisher=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref><ref name=\"WCS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spacesecurity.org/files/WorldCivilSats2006.xls|title=World Civil Satellites 1957-2006|publisher=Space Security Index |accessdate=2009-12-06|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718022840/http://www.spacesecurity.org/files/WorldCivilSats2006.xls|archivedate=18 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* [[1965 in spaceflight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik}}\n{{Orbital launches in 1965}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosmos 0095}}\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 1965]]\n[[Category:Kosmos satellites]]\n[[Category:Dnepropetrovsk Sputnik program]]\n\n{{USSR-spacecraft-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CRS-20", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kosmos_95"}
